An irritant whine edged his mother's voice as David sat down across from her in the sunny breakfast room that overlooked their back lawn and private stream.\~ The scowl which accompanied the whine drew sharp lines down her forehead toward her nose.\~ 
A vein on her left hand had taken on the hue of rusty iron.\~ She wore something pink and lacy, her yellow hair fluffed up.\~ Her lavender perfume enveloped the table.
\par She said:\~ "I wish you wouldn't take that awful knife to camp, Davey.\~ What in heaven's name will you do with such a thing?\~ I think your father was quite mad to give you such a dangerous instrument."
\par Her left hand jingled the little bell to summon the cook with David's cereal.
\par David stared down at the table while cook's pink hand put a bowl there.\~ The cream in the bowl was almost the same yellow as the tablecloth.\~ The bowl gave off the odor of the fresh strawberries sliced into the cereal.\~ David adjusted his napkin.

\par His mother said:\~ "Well?"
\par Sometimes her questions were not meant to be answered, but "}{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Well?" }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 signaled pressure.
\par He sighed.\~ "Mother, everyone at camp has a knife."
\par "Why?"
\par "To cut things, carve wood, stuff like that."
\par He began eating.\~ One hour.\~ That could be endured.
\par "To cut your fingers off!" she said.\~ "I simply refuse to let you take such a dangerous thing."
\par He swallowed a mouthful of cereal while he studied her the way he had seen his father do it, letting his mind sort out the possible countermoves.\~ A breeze shook the trees bordering the lawn behind her.
\par "Well?" she insisted.
\par "What do I do?" he asked.\~ "Every time I need a knife I'll have to borrow one from one of the other guys."
\par He took another mouthful of cereal, savoring the acid of the strawberries while he waited for her to assess the impossibility of keeping him knifeless at camp.\~ David knew how her mind worked.\~
 She had been Prosper Morgenstern before she had married Dad.\~ The Morgensterns always had the best.\~ If he was going to have a knife }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 anyway}{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588  --
\par She put flame to a cigarette, her hand jerking.\~ The smoke emerged from her mouth in spurts.
\par David went on eating.
\par She put the cigarette aside, said:\~ "Oh, very well.\~ But you must be extremely careful."
\par "Just like Dad showed me," he said.
\par She stared at him, a finger of her left hand tapping a soft drumbeat on the table.\~ The movement set the diamonds on her wristwatch clasp aflame.\~ She said:\~ "I don't know what I'll do with both of my men gone."
\par "Dad'll be halfway to Washington by now."
\par "And you in that awful camp."
\par "It's the best camp there is."
\par "I guess so.\~ You know, Davey, we all may have to move to the East."
\par David nodded.\~ His father had moved them to the Carmel Valley and gone back into private practice after the last election.\~ He commuted up the Peninsula to the city three days a week.\~ Sometimes Prosper joined him there for a weekend.\~
 They kept an apartment in the city and a maid-caretaker.
\par But yesterday his father had received a telephone call from someone important in the government.\~ There had been other calls and a sense of excitement in the house.\~ Howard Marshall had been offered an important position in the State Department.
\par David said:\~ "It's funny, y'know?"
\par "What is, dear?"
\par "Dad's going to Washington and so am I."
\par She smiled.\~ "Different Washingtons."
\par "Both named for the same man."
\par "Indeed they were."
\par Mrs. Parma glided into the breakfast room, said:\~ "Excuse me, madam.\~ I have had Peter put the young sir's equipage into the car.\~ Will there be anything else?"
\par "Thank you, Mrs. Parma.\~ That will be all."
\par David waited until Mrs. Parma had gone, said:\~ "That book about the camp said they have some Indian counselors.\~ Will they look like Mrs. Parma?'
\par "Davey!\~ Don't they teach you }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 anything }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 in that school?"
\par "I know they're different Indians.\~ I just wondered if they, you know, looked like her, if that's why we called our Indians. . . ."
\par "What a strange idea."\~ She shook her head, arose.\~ "There are times when you remind me of your grandfather Morgenstern.\~ He used to insist the Indians were the lost tribe of Israel."\~ 
She hesitated, one hand lingering on the table, her gaze focused on the knife at David's waist.\~ "You }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 will }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
be careful with that awful knife?"
\par "I'll do just like Dad said.\~ }{\insrsid8201588 Don't worry."
