David, his mind still drugged with sleep, came wide awake as he stepped out the door into the cold night.\~ Shivering, he stared at the man who had awakened him -- }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 the Chief.}{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par "What is it, Chief?"
\par "Shhhh."\~ Katsuk touched the roll of clothing.\~ "Get dressed."
\par More from the cold than any other reason, David obeyed.\~ Tree branches whipped in the wind above the cabin, filled the night with fearful shapes.
\par "Is it an initiation, Chief?"
\par "Shhh, be very quiet."
\par "Why?"
\par "We were photographed together.\~ We must become spirit brothers.\~ There is a ceremony."
\par "What about the other guys?"
\par "You have been chosen."
\par Katsuk fought down sudden pity for this boy, this Innocent.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Why pity anyone?\~ }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
He realized the moonlight had cut at his heart.\~ For some reason, it made him think of the Shaker Church where his relatives had taken him as a child -- hoquat church!\~ He heard the voices chanting in his memory:\~ }{
\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 "Begat, begat, begat. . . ."}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par David whispered:\~ "I don't understand.\~ What're we doing?"
\par The stars staring down at him, the wind in the trees, all carried forboding.\~ He felt frightened.\~ A gap in the trees beyond the porch revealed a great bush of stars standing out against the night.\~ David stared into the shadows of the porch.\~
 Why wasn't the Chief answering?
\par David tightened his belt, felt the knife in its sheath at his waist.\~ If the Chief were planning something bad, he'd have removed the knife.\~ That was a real weapon.\~ Daniel Boone had killed a bear with a blade no bigger than this one.
\par "What're we going to do?" David pressed.
\par "A ceremony of spirit brotherhood," Katsuk said.\~ He felt the truth in his words.\~ There would be a ceremony and a joining, a shape that occurred out of darkness, a mark on the earth and an incantation to the real spirits.
\par David still hesitated, thinking this was an Indian.\~ They were strange people.\~ He thought of Mrs. Parma.\~ Different Indian, but both mysterious.
\par David pulled his jacket close around him.\~ The cold air had raised goose pimples on his skin.\~ He felt both frightened and excited.\~ An Indian.
\par He said:\~ "You're not dressed."
\par "I'm dressed for the ceremony."
\par Silently, Katsuk prayed:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 "O Life Giver, now that you have seen the way apart of your all-powerful being goes}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 . . . ."

\par David sensed the man's tensions, the air of secrecy.\~ But no place could be safer than this wilderness camp with that cog railroad the only way to get here.
\par He asked:\~ "Aren't you cold?"
\par "I am used to this.\~ You must hurry after me now.\~ We haven't much time."
\par Katsuk stepped down off the porch.\~ The boy followed.
\par "Where are we going?"
\par "To the top of the ridge."
\par David hurried to keep in step.\~ "Why?"
\par "I have prepared a place there for you to be initiated into a very old ceremony of my people."
\par "Because of the photographs?"
\par "Yes."
\par "I didn't think Indians believed in that stuff anymore."
\par "Even you will believe."
\par David tucked his shirt more firmly into his belt, felt the knife.\~ The knife gave him a feeling of confidence.\~ He stumbled in his hurry to keep up.
\par Without looking back, Katsuk felt the boy's tensions relax.\~ There had been a moment back on the porch when rebellion had radiated from the Innocent.\~ The boy's eyes had been uncertain, wet and smooth in their darkness.\~ 
The bitter acid of fear had been in the air.\~ But now the boy would follow.\~ He was enthralled.\~ The center of the universe carried the power of a magnet for that Innocent.
\par David felt his heart beating rapidly from exertion.\~ He smelled rancid oil from the Chief.\~ The man's skin glistened when moonlight touched it, as though he had greased his body.
\par "How far is it?" David asked.
\par "Three thousand and eighty-one paces."
\par "How far is that?"
\par "A bit over a mile."
\par "Did you have to dress like that?"
\par "Yes."
\par "What if it rains?"
\par "I will not notice."
\par "Why're we going so fast?"
\par "We need the moonlight for the ceremony.\~ Be silent now and stay close."
\par Katsuk felt brass laughter in his chest, picked up the pace.\~ The smell of newly cut cedar drifted on the air.\~ The rich odor of cedar oils carried an omen message from the days when that tree had sheltered his people.
\par David stumbled over a root, regained his balance.
\par The trail pushed through mottled darkness -- black broken by sharp slashes of moonlight.\~ The bobbing patch of loincloth ahead of him carried a strange dream quality to David.\~ 
When moonlight reached it, the man's skin glistened, but his black hair drank the light, was one with the shadows.
\par "Will the other guys be initiated?" David asked.
\par "I told you that you are the only one."
\par "Why?"
\par "You will understand soon.\~ Do not talk."
\par Katsuk hoped the silence brought by that rebuke would endure.\~ Like all hoquat, the boy talked too much.\~ There could be no reprieve for such a one.
\par "I keep stumbling," David muttered.
\par "Walk as I walk."
\par Katsuk measured the trail by the feeling of it underfoot:\~ soft earth, a dampness where a spring surfaced, spruce cones, the hard lacery of roots polished by many feet. . . .
\par He began to think of his sister and of his former life before Katsuk.\~ He felt the spirits of air and earth draw close, riding this moonlight, bringing the memory of all the lost tribes.
\par David thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Walk as he walks?}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par The man moved with sliding panther grace, almost noiseless.\~ The trail grew steep, tangled with more roots, slippery underfoot, but still the man moved as though he saw every surface change, every rock and root.
\par David became aware of the wet odors all around:\~ rotting wood, musks, bitter acridity of ferns.\~ Wet leaves brushed his cheeks.\~ Limbs and vines dragged at him.\~ He heard 
falling water, louder and louder -- a river cascading in its gorge off to the right.\~ He hoped the sound covered his clumsiness but feared the Chief could hear him and was laughing.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Walk as I walk!}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par How could the Chief even see anything in this dark?
\par The trail entered a bracken clearing.\~ David saw peaks directly ahead, snow on them streaked by moonlight, a bright sieve of stars close overhead.
\par Katsuk stared upward as he walked.\~ The peaks appeared to be stitched upon the sky by the stars.\~ He allowed this moment its time to flow through him, renewing the spirit message:\~ "}{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
I am Tamanawis speaking to you}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 . . . ."
\par He began to sing the names of his dead, sent the names outward into Sky World.\~ A falling star swept over the clearing -- another, then another and another until the sky flamed with them.
\par Katsuk fell silent in wonder.\~ This was no astronomical display to be explained by the hoquat magic science; this was a message from the past.
\par The boy spoke close behind; "Wow!\~ Look at the falling stars.\~ Did you make a wish?"
\par "I made a wish."
\par "What were you singing?"
\par "A song of my people."
\par Katsuk, the omen of the stars strong within him, saw the charcoal slash of path and the clearing as an arena within which he would begin creating a memory maker, a death song for the ways of the past, a holy obscenity to awe the hoquat world.
\par "Skagajek!" he shouted.\~ "I am the shaman spirit come to drive the sickness from this world!"
\par David, hearing the strange words, lost his footing, almost fell, and was once again afraid.
