The immensity of the wilderness universe around David, the mystery of this midnight hike to some strange ritual, began to tell on him.\~ His body was wet with perspiration, chilled in every breeze.\~ His feet were sopping with trail dew.\~
 The Chief, an awesome figure in this setting, had taken on a new character.\~ He walked with such steady confidence that David sensed all the accumulated woods knowledge compressed into each movement.\~ The man was Deerstalker.\~
 He was Ultimate Woodsman.\~ He was a person who could survive in this wilderness.
\par David began dropping farther and farther behind.\~ The Chief became a gray blur ahead.
\par Without turning, Katsuk called:\~ "Keep up."
\par David quickened his steps.
\par Something barked "Yap-yap!" in the trees off to his right.\~ A sudden motion of smoky wings glided across him, almost touched his head.\~ David ducked, hurried to close the gap between himself and that bobbing white loincloth.
\par Abruptly, Katsuk stopped.\~ David almost ran into him.
\par Katsuk looked at the moon.\~ It moved over the trees, illuminating crags and rock spurs on the far slope.\~ His feet had measured out the distance.\~ This was the place.
\par David asked:\~ "Why'd we stop?"
\par "This is the place."
\par "Here?\~ What's here?"
\par Katsuk thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 How is it the hoquat all do this?\~ They always prefer mouth-talk to body-talk.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par He ignored the boy's question.\~ What answer could there be?\~ This ignorant Innocent had failed to read the signs.
\par Katsuk squatted, faced the trail's downhill side.\~ This had been an elk trail for centuries, the route between salt water and high meadows.\~ The earth had been cut out deeply by the hooves.\~ Ferns and moss grew from the side of the trail.\~ 
Katsuk felt into the growth.\~ His fingers went as surely as though guided by sight.\~ Gently, gently, he pulled the fronds aside.\~ Yes!\~ This was the place he had marked out.
\par He began chanting, low-voiced in the ancient tongue:
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 "Hoquat, let your body accept the consecrated arrow.\~ Let pride fill your soul at the touch of my sharp and biting point.\~ Your soul will turn toward the sky}{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 . . . ."
\par David listened to the unintelligible words.\~ He could not see the man's hands in the fern shadows, but the movements bothered him and he could not identify the reason.\~ He wanted to ask what was happening but felt an odd constraint.\~ 
The chanted words were full of clickings and gruntings.
\par The man fell silent.
\par Katsuk opened the pouch at his waist, removed a pinch of the consecrated white duck down.\~ His fingers trembled.\~ It must be done correctly.\~ Any mistake would bring disaster.
\par David, his eyes adjusting to the gloom, began to make out the shadowy movement of hands in the ferns.\~ Something white reflected moonlight there.\~ He squatted beside the man, cleared his throat.
\par "What're you doing?"
\par "I am writing my name upon the earth.\~ I must do that before you can learn my name."
\par "Isn't your name Charlie something?"
\par "That is not my name."
\par "Oh?"\~ David thought about this.\~ Not his name?\~ Then:\~ "Were you singing just now?"
\par "Yes."
\par "What were you singing?"
\par "A song for you -- to give you a name."
\par "I already }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 have }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 a name."
\par "You do not have a secret name given between us, the most powerful name a person can have."
\par Katsuk smoothed dirt over the pinch of down.\~ He sensed }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Kuschtaliute, }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
the hidden tongue of the land otter, working through his hand upon the dirt, guiding each movement.\~ The power grew in him.
\par David shivered in the cold, said:\~ "This isn't much fun.\~ Is this all there is to it?"
\par "It is important if we are to share our names."
\par "Am I supposed to do something?"
\par "Yes."
\par "What?"
\par Katsuk arose.\~ He sensed tensions in his fingers where Kuschtaliute still controlled his muscles.\~ Bits of dirt clung to his skin.\~ The spirit power of this moment went all through his flesh.\~ }{
\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 "I am Tamanawis speaking to you}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 . . . ."
\par He said:\~ "You will stand now and face the moon."
\par "Why?"
\par "Do it."
\par "What if I don't?"
\par "You will anger the spirits."
\par Something in the man's tone dried David's mouth.\~ He said:\~ "I want to go back now."
\par "First, you must stand and face the moon."
\par "Then can we go back?"
\par "Then we can go."
\par "Well . . . okay.\~ But I think this is kind of dumb."
\par David stood.\~ He felt the wind, a forboding of rain in it.\~ His mind was filled suddenly with memories of a childish game he and his friends had played among the creekside trees near his home:\~ }{
\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Cowboys and Indians.\~ }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 What would that game mean to this man?
\par Scenes and words tumbled through David's mind:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Bang!\~ Bang!\~ You're dead!\~ Dead injun cowboy injun dead.\~ }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
And Mrs. Parma calling him to lunch.\~ But he and his friends had scratched out a cave in the creek bank and had hidden there, suppressing giggles in the mildew smell of cave dirt and the voice of Mrs. Parma calling and everyth
ing stirring in his head -- memory and this moment in the wilderness, all become one -- moon, dark trees moved by the wind, moonlit clouds beyond a distant hill, the damp odor of earth. . . .
\par The man spoke close behind him:\~ "You can hear the river down there.\~ We are near water.\~ Spirits gather near water.\~ Once, long ago, we hunted spirit power as children seek a toy.\~ But you hoquat came and you changed that.\~
 I was a grown man before I felt Tamanawis within me."
\par David trembled.\~ He had not expected words of such odd beauty.\~ They were like prayer.\~ He felt the warmth of the man's body behind him, the breath touching his head.
\par The voice continued in a harsh tone:
\par "We ruined it, you know.\~ We distrusted and hated each other instead of our common foe.\~ Foreign ideas and words clotted our minds with illusion, stole our flesh from us.\~ The white man came upon us with a face like a golden mask with pits for eyes.\~ 
We were frozen before him.\~ Shapes came out of the darkness.\~ They were part of darkness and against it -- flesh and antiflesh -- and we had no ritual for this.\~ We mistook immobility for peace and we were punished."
\par David tried to swallow in a dry throat.\~ This did not have the sound of ritual.\~ The man spoke with an accent of education and knowledge.\~ His words conveyed a sense of accusation.
\par "Do you hear me?" Katsuk asked.
\par For a moment, David failed to realize the question had been directed at him.\~ The man's voice had carried such a feeling of speaking to spirits.
\par Katsuk raised his voice:\~ "Do you hear me?"
\par David jumped.\~ "Yes."
\par "Now, repeat after me exactly what I say."
\par David nodded.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "I am Hoquat."
\par "What?"
\par "I am Hoquat!"
\par "I am Hoquat?"\~ David could not keep a questioning inflection from his voice.
\par "I am the message from Soul Catcher," Katsuk said.
\par In a flat voice, David repeated it:\~ "I am the message from Soul Catcher."
\par "It is done," Katsuk said.\~ "You have repeated the ritual correctly.\~ From this moment, your name is Hoquat."
\par "Does it mean something?" David asked.\~ He started to turn, but a hand on his shoulder restrained him.
\par "It is the name my people gave to something that floats far out on the water, something strange that cannot be identified.\~ It is the name we gave to your people because you came that way to us from the water."
\par David did not like the hand on his shoulder, but feared saying anything about it.\~ He felt that his being, his private flesh, had been offended.\~ Opposing forces struggled in him.\~ He had been prepared for an event whi
ch he could almost see, and this ritual failed to satisfy him.
\par He asked:\~ "Is that all there is to it?"
\par "No.\~ It is time for you to learn my name."
\par "You said we could go."
\par "We will go soon."
\par "Well . . . what's your name?"
\par "Katsuk."
\par David fought down a shudder.\~ "What's that mean?"
\par "Many, many things.\~ It is the center of the universe."
\par "Is it an Indian word?"
\par "Indian!\~ I am sick with being Indian, with living out a five-hundred-year-old mistake!"
\par The hand on David's shoulder gripped him hard, shook him with each word.\~ David went very still.\~ Suddenly, he knew for the first time he was in danger.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Katsuk.\~ }{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 It had an ugly sound.\~ He could not understand why, but the name suggested deadly peril.\~ He whispered:\~ "Can we go now?"
\par Katsuk said:\~ "Mamook memaloost!\~ Kechgi tsuk achat kamooks. . . ."
\par In the old tongue, he promised it all:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 I will sacrifice this Innocent.\~ I will give him to the spirits who protect me.\~ 
I will send him into the underplaces and his eyes will be the two eyes of the worm.\~ His heart will not beat.\~ His mouth}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 . . . ."
\par "What're you saying?" David demanded.
\par But Katsuk ignored him, went on to the end of it.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Katsuk makes this promise in the name of Soul Catcher."}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par David said:\~ "I don't understand you.\~ What was all that?"
\par "You are the Innocent," Katsuk said.\~ "But I am Katsuk.\~ I am the middle of everything.\~ I live everywhere.\~ I see you hoquat all around.\~ You live like dogs.\~ You are great liars.\~ You see the moon and call it a moon.\~ 
You think that makes it a moon.\~ But I have seen it all with my good eye and recognize without words when a thing exists."
\par "I want to go back now."
\par Katsuk shook his head.\~ "We all want to go back, Innocent Hoquat.\~ We want the place where we can deal with our revelation and weep and punish our senses uselessly.\~ You talk and your world sours me.\~
 You have only words that tell me of the world you would have if I permitted you to have it.\~ But I have brought you here.\~ I will give you back your own knowledge of what the universe knows.\~ I will make you know and feel.\~
 You really will understand.\~ You will be surprised.\~ What you learn will be what you thought you already knew."
\par "Please, can't we go now?"
\par "You wish to run away.\~ You think there is no place within you to receive what I will give you.\~ But it will be driven into your heart by the thing itself.\~ What folly you have learned!\~ You think you can ignore such things as I will teach.\~ 
You think your senses cannot accept the universe without compromise.\~ Hoquat, I promise you this:\~ you will see directly through to the thing at its beginning.\~ You will hear the wilderness without names.\~
 You will feel colors and shapes and the temper of this world.\~ You will see the tyranny.\~ It will fill you with awe and fear."
\par Gently, David tried to pull away from the restraining hand, to put distance between himself and these terrifying words of almost-meaning.\~ Indians should not speak this way!
\par But the hand shifted down to his left arm, held it painfully.
\par No longer trying to conceal his fear, David said:\~ "You're hurting me!"
\par The pressure eased, but not enough to release him.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "We have shared names.\~ You will stay."
\par David held himself motionless.\~ Confusion filled his mind.\~ He felt that he had been kicked, injured in a way that locked all his muscles.\~ Katsuk released his arm.\~ Still David remained fixed in that position.
\par Fighting dryness in his mouth, David said:\~ "You're trying to scare me.\~ That's it, isn't it?\~ That's the initiation.\~ The other guys are out there waiting to laugh."
\par Katsuk ignored the words.\~ He felt the spirit power grow and grow.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 "l am Tamanawis speaking to you}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588  --"\~
 With slow, deliberate movements, he took an elkhide thong from his pouch, whipped it over the boy's shoulders, bound his arms tightly to his body.
\par David began twisting, struggling to escape.\~ "Hey!\~ Stop that!\~ You're hurting me!"
\par Katsuk grabbed the twisting hands, pinioned the wrists in a loop of the thong.
\par David struggled with the strength of terror, but the hands tying him could not be resisted.\~ The thong bit painfully into his flesh.
\par "Please stop it," David pleaded.\~ "What're you doing?"
\par "Shut up, Hoquat!"
\par This was a new and savage voice, as powerful as the hands which held him.
\par Chest heaving, David fell silent.\~ He was wet with perspiration and the moment he stopped struggling, the wind chilled him.\~ 
He felt his captor remove the knife and sheath, working the belt out with harsh, jerking motions, then reclasping the belt without putting it into its loops.
\par Katsuk bent close to the boy, face demoniac in the moonlight.\~ His voice was a blare of passion:\~ "Hoquat!\~ Do what I tell you to do, or I will kill you immediately."\~ He brandished David's knife.
\par David nodded without control of the motion, unable to speak.\~ A tide of bitter acid came into his throat.\~ He continued to nod until Katsuk shook him.
\par "Hoquat, do you understand me?"
\par He could barely manage the word:\~ "Yes."
\par And David thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 "I'm being kidnapped!\~ It was all a trick."}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par All the horror stories he'd heard about murdered kidnap victims flooded into his mind, set his body jerking with terror.\~ He felt betrayed, shamed at his own stupidity for falling into such a trap.
\par Katsuk produced another thong, passed it beneath David's arms, around his chest, knotted it, and took the free end in one hand.\~ He said:\~ "We have a long way to go before daylight.\~ 
Follow me swiftly or I will bury your body beside the trail and go on alone."
\par Turning, Katsuk jerked the rope, headed at a trot toward the dark wall of trees across the bracken clearing.
\par David, the stench of his own fear in his nostrils, stumbled into motion to keep from being pulled off his feet.
