About an hour after sunrise, Katsuk led Hoquat at a shambling trot to the foot of the shale slope he had set as his first night's goal.\~ The instant they stopped, the boy collapsed on the ground.\~ 
Katsuk ignored this and concentrated on studying the slope, noting the marks of a recent slide.
\par At the top of the slope a stand of spruce and willow concealed a notch in the cliff.\~ The trees masked a cave and the spring which fed the trees.\~ The cliff loomed as a gray eminence behind the trees.\~ 
The slide made it appear no one could climb to the notch.
\par Katsuk felt his heart beating strongly.\~ Vapor formed at his mouth when he breathed.\~ The morning was cold, although there would be sunlight here below the cliff later.\~ The sharp smell of mint scratched at his awareness.\~
 Mint fed by the runoff of the spring protruded from rocks at the bottom of the slide.\~ The odor reminded Katsuk that he was hungry and thirsty.
\par That would pass, he knew.
\par Even if the searchers used dogs, Katsuk did not believe they would get this far.\~ He had used a scent-killer of his own making many times during the night, had broken trail four times by wading into streams, starting one way, killing the scent, then dou
bling back.
\par The low light of morning set the world into sharp relief.\~ Off to his right at the edge of the rockslide red fireweed plumes swayed on the slope.\~ A flying squirrel glided down the slope into the trees.\~ Katsuk felt the flow of life all around 
him, glanced down at Hoquat sprawled in a bracken clump, a picture of complete fatigue.
\par What a hue and cry would be raised for this one.\~ What a prize!\~ What headlines!\~ A message that could not be denied.
\par Katsuk glanced up at the pale sky.\~ The pursuers would use helicopters and other aircraft, of course.\~ They would be starting out soon.\~ Just about now, they would be discovering at the camp what had been done to them.\~ 
The serious, futile hoquat with their ready-made lives, their plastic justifications for existence, would come upon something new and terrifying:\~ a note from Katsuk.\~ They would know that the }{
\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 place of safety }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 in which their spirits cowered had been breached.
\par He tugged at the thong that linked him to Hoquat, got only a lifted head and questioning stare from eyes bright with fear and fatigue.\~ Tear streaks lined the boy's face.
\par Katsuk steeled himself against sympathy.\~ His thoughts went to all the innocents of his own people who had died beneath guns and sabers, died of starvation, of germ-laden blankets deliberately sold to the tribes to kill them off.
\par "Get up," Katsuk said.
\par Hoquat struggled to his feet, stood swaying, shivering.\~ His clothes were wet with trail dew.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "We are going to climb this rock slope.\~ It is a dangerous climb.\~ Watch where I put my feet.\~ Put your feet exactly where I have.\~ If you make a mistake, you will start a slide.\~ I will save myself.\~ You will be buried in the slide.
\~ Is this understood?"
\par Hoquat nodded.
\par Katsuk hesitated.\~ Did the boy have sufficient reserves of strength to do this?\~ The nod of agreement could have been fearful obedience without understanding.
\par But what did it matter?\~ The spirits would preserve this innocent for the consecrated arrow, or they would take him.\~ Either way, the message would be heard.\~ There was no reprieve.
\par The boy stood waiting for the nightmare journey to continue.\~ A dangerous climb?\~ All right.\~ What difference did it make?\~ Except that he must survive this, must live to escape.\~ The madman had called him Hoquat, had f
orced him to answer to that name.\~ More than anything else, this concentrated a core of fury in the boy.
\par He thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 My name is David.\~ David, not Hoquat.\~ David-not-Hoquat.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par His legs ached.\~ His feet were wet and sore.\~ He felt that if he could just close his eyes right here he could sleep standing up.\~ When he blinked, his eyelids felt rough against his eyes.\~ 
His left arm was sore where a long red abrasion had been dragged across his skin by the rough bark of a tree.\~ It had torn both his jacket and shirt.\~ The madman had cursed him then:\~ a savage voice out of darkness.
\par The night had been a cold nightmare in a black pit of trees.\~ Now he saw morning's rose vapors on the peaks, but the nightmare continued.
\par Katsuk gave a commanding tug on the thong, studied the boy's response.\~ Too slow.\~ The fool would kill them both on that slide.
\par "What is your name?" Katsuk asked.
\par The voice was low, defiant:\~ "David Marshall."
\par Without change of expression, Katsuk delivered a sharp backhand blow to the boy's cheek, measuring it to sting but not injure.\~ "What is your name?"
\par "You }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 know }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 my name!"
\par "Say your name."
\par "It's Dav --"
\par Again, Katsuk struck him.
\par The boy stared at him, defiant, fighting back tears.
\par Katsuk thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 No reprieve . . . no reprieve}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588  --
\par "I know what you want me to say," the boy muttered.\~ His jaws pulsed with the effort of holding back tears.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 No reprieve.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par "Your name," Katsuk insisted, touching the knife at his waist.\~ The boy's eyes followed the movement.
\par "Hoquat."\~ It was muttered, almost unintelligible.
\par "Louder."
\par The boy opened his mouth, screamed:\~ "Hoquat!"
\par Katsuk said:\~ "Now, we will climb."
\par He turned, went up the shale slope.\~ He placed each foot with care:\~ now on a flat slab jutting from the slide, now on a sloping buttress which seemed anchored in the mountain.\~ Once, a rock shifted under his testing foot.\~
 Pebbles bounded down into the trees while he waited, poised to jump if the slope went.\~ The rocks remained in place, but he sensed the trembling uncertainty of the whole structure.\~ Cautiously, he went on up.
\par At the beginning of the climb, he watched to see that Hoquat made each step correctly, found the boy occupied with bent-head concentration, step for step, a precise imitation.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Good.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par Katsuk concentrated on his own climbing then.
\par At the top, he grasped a willow bough, pulled them both into the shelter of the trees.
\par In the shaded yellow silence there, Katsuk allowed the oil-smooth flow of elation to fill him.\~ He had done this thing!\~ He had taken the Innocent and was safe for the moment.\~ He had all the survival seasons before him:\~
 the season of the midge, of the cattail flowering, of salal ripening, of salmonberries, the season of grubs and ants -- a season for each food.
\par Finally, there would be a season for the vision he must dream before he could leave the Innocent's flesh to be swallowed by the spirits underground.
\par Hoquat had collapsed to the ground once more, unaware of what waited him.
\par Abruptly, a thunderous flapping of wings brought Katsuk whirling to the left.\~ The boy sat up, trembling.\~ Katsuk peered upward between the willow branches at a flight of ravens.\~ They circled the lower slopes, then climbed into the sunlight.\~ 
Katsuk's gaze followed the birds as they swam in the sky sea.\~ A smile of satisfaction curved his lips.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 An omen!\~ Surely an omen!}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par Deerflies sang in the shadows behind him.\~ He heard water dripping at the spring.
\par Katsuk turned.
\par At the sound of the ravens, the boy had retreated into the tree shadows as far as the thong would allow.\~ He sat there now, staring at Katsuk, and his forehead and hair caught the first sunlight in the gloom like a trout flashing in a pool.
\par The Innocent must be hidden before the searchers took to the sky, Katsuk thought.\~ He pushed past the boy, found the game trail which his people had known here for centuries.
\par "Come," he said, tugging at the thong.
\par Katsuk felt the boy get up and follow.
\par At the rock pool where the spring bubbled from the cliff, Katsuk dropped the thong, stretched out, and buried his face in the cold water.\~ He drank deeply.
\par The boy sprawled beside him, would have pitched head foremost into the pool if Katsuk had not caught him.
\par "Thirsty," Hoquat whispered.
\par "Then drink."
\par Katsuk held the boy's shoulder while he drank.\~ Hoquat gasped and sputtered, coming up at last with his face and blond hair dripping.
\par "We will go into the cave now," Katsuk said.
\par The cave was a pyramidal black hole above the pool, its entrance hidden from the sky by a mossy overhang which dripped condensation.\~ Katsuk studied the cave mouth a moment for sign that an animal might be occupying it, saw no sign.\~ 
He tugged at the thong, led Hoquat up the rock ledge beside the pool and into the cave.
\par "I smell something," the boy said.
\par Katsuk sniffed:\~ There were many old odors -- animal dung, fur, fungus.\~ All of them were old.\~ Bear denned here because it was dry, but none had been here for at least a year.
\par "Bear den last year," he said.
\par He waited for his eyes to adjust to the gloom, found a rock spur too high up on the cave's wall for the boy to reach with his tied hands, secured the end of the thong on the spur.
\par The boy stood with his back against the rock wall.\~ His gaze followed every move Katsuk made.\~ Katsuk wondered what he was thinking.\~ The eyes appeared feverish in their intensity.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "We will rest here today.\~ There is no one to hear you if you shout.\~ But if you shout, I will kill you.\~ I will kill you at the first outcry.\~ You must learn to obey me completely.\~ You must learn to depend on me for your life.\~ 
Is that understood?"
\par The boy stared at him, unmoving, unspeaking.
\par Katsuk gripped the boy's chin, peered into his eyes, met rage and defiance.
\par "Your name is Hoquat," Katsuk said.
\par The boy jerked his chin free.
\par Katsuk put a finger gently on the red mark on Hoquat's cheek from the two blows at the rockslide.\~ Speaking softly, he said:\~ "Do not make me strike you again.\~ We should not have that between us."
\par The boy blinked.\~ Tears formed in the corners of his eyes, but he shook them out with an angry gesture.
\par Still in that soft voice, Katsuk said:\~ "Answer to your name when I ask you.\~ What is your name now?"
\par "Hoquat."\~ Sullen, but clear.
\par "Good."
\par Katsuk went to the cave mouth, paused there to let his senses test the area.\~ Shadows were shortening at the end of the notch as the sun climbed higher.\~ Bright yellow skunk cabbages poked from the shadowed water at the lower end of the spring pool.

\par It bothered him that he had struck Hoquat, although strong body-talk had been required then.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Do I pity Hoquat? he wondered.\~ Why pity anyone?}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par But the boy had showed surprising strength.\~ He had spirit in him.\~ Hoquat was not a whiner.\~ He was not a coward.\~ His innocence lay within a real person whose center of being remained yet unformed but was gaining power.\~ 
It would be easy to admire this Innocent.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Must I admire the victim? }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Katsuk wondered.
\par That would make this thing all the more difficult.\~ Perhaps it would occur, though, as a special test of Katsuk's purpose.\~ One did not slay an innocent out of casual whim.\~ One who wore the mantle of Soul Catcher dared not do a wrong thing.\~ 
If it were done, it must fit the demands of the spirit world.
\par Still, it would be a heavy burden to kill someone you admired.\~ Too heavy a burden?\~ Without the need for immediate decision, he could not say.\~ This was not an issue he wanted to confront.
\par Again, he wondered:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Why was I chosen for this?}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par Had it occurred in a way similar to the way he had chosen Hoquat?\~ Out of what mysterious necessities did the spirit world act?\~ Had the behavior of the white world become at last too much to bear?\~ Certainly that must be the answer.
\par He felt that he should call out from the cave mouth where he stood, shouting in a voice that could be heard all the way to the ocean:
\par "}{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 You down there!\~ See what you have done to us!"}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par He stood lost in reverie and wondered presently if he might have shouted.\~ But the hoard of life all around gave no sign of disturbance.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 If I admire Hoquat, }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 he thought, }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
I must do it only to strengthen my decision.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
