David shuddered with aversion to his surroundings.\~ The gray-green gloom of the cave, the wet smoothness o
f rock walls at the sunlit mouth which his thong leash would not permit him to reach, the animal odors, the dance of dripping water outside -- all tormented him.
\par He was a battleground of emotions:\~ something near hysteria compounded of hunger, dread, shuddering uncertainty, fatigue, rage.
\par Katsuk came back into the cave, a black silhouette against sunlight.\~ He wore the Russell knife at his waist, one hand on the handle.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 My knife, }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 David thought.\~ He began to tremble.
\par "You are not sleeping," Katsuk said.
\par No answer.
\par "You have questions?" Katsuk asked.
\par "Why?" David whispered.
\par Katsuk nodded but remained silent.
\par The boy said:\~ "You're holding me for ransom, is that it?"
\par Katsuk shook his head.\~ "Ransom?\~ Do you think I could ransom you for an entire world?"
\par The boy shook his head, not understanding.
\par "Perhaps I could ransom you for an end to all hoquat mistakes," Katsuk said.
\par "What're you. . . ."
\par "Ahhh, you wonder if I'm crazy.\~ Drunk, maybe.\~ Crazy, drunken Indian.\~ You see, I know all the cliches."
\par "I just asked why."\~ Voice low.
\par "I'm an ignorant, incompetent savage, that's why.\~ If I have a string of degrees after my name, that must be an accident.\~ Or I probably have white blood in me, eh?\~ Hoquat blood?\~ But I drink too much.\~ I'm lazy.\~ I don't l
ike to work and be industrious.\~ Have I missed anything?\~ Any other cliches?\~ Oh, yes -- I'm bloodthirsty, too."
\par "But I just --"
\par "You wonder about ransom.\~ I think you have made all the mistakes a hoquat should be permitted."
\par "Are you . . . crazy?"
\par Katsuk chuckled.\~ "Maybe, just a little."
\par "Are you going to kill me?"\~ Barely whispered.
\par "Go to sleep and don't ask stupid questions."\~ He indicated the cave floor, clumps of dry moss which could be kicked into a bed.
\par The boy took a quavering breath.\~ "I don't want to sleep."
\par "You will obey me."\~ Katsuk pointed to the floor, kicked some of the moss into position at the boy's feet.
\par Every movement a signal of defiance, Hoquat knelt, rolled onto his side, his tied hands pressed against the rock wall of the cave.\~ His eyes remained open, glaring up at Katsuk.
\par "Close your eyes."
\par "I can't."
\par Katsuk noted the fatigue signs, the trembling, the glazed eyes.\~ "Why can't you?"
\par "I just can't."
\par "Why?"
\par "Are you going to kill me?"\~ Stronger that time.
\par Katsuk shook his head.
\par "Why are you doing this to me?" the boy demanded.
\par "Doing what?"
\par "Kidnapping me, treating me like this."
\par "Treating you like what?"
\par "You know!"
\par "But you have received ordinary treatment for an }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Indian.\~ }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Have our hands not been tied?\~ Have we not been dragged where 
we would rather not go?\~ Have we not been brutalized and forced to take names we did not want?"
\par "But why me?"
\par "Ahhhh, why you!\~ The cry of innocence from every age."
\par Katsuk pressed his eyes tightly closed.\~ His mind felt damned with evil sensations.\~ He opened his eyes, knew he had become that }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 other person, }{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 the one who used Charles Hobuhet's education and experiences, but with a brain working in a different way.\~ Ancient instincts pulsed in his flesh.
\par "What'd I ever do to you?" the boy asked.
\par "Precisely," Katsuk said.\~ "You have done nothing to me.\~ That is why I chose you."
\par "You talk crazy!"
\par "You think I have caught the hoquat disease, eh?\~ You think I have only words, that I must find words to pin down what cannot be cut into word shapes.\~ Your mouth bites at the universe.\~ You give tongue to noises.\~ I do not do that.\~
 I send another kind of message.\~ I draw a design upon the emotions.\~ My design will rise up inside people where they have no defenses.\~ They will not be able to shut their ears and deny they heard me.\~ I tell you, they will hear Katsuk!"
\par "You're crazy!"
\par "It is odd," Katsuk mused.\~ "You may be one of the few people in the world who will not hear me."
\par "You're crazy!\~ You're crazy!"
\par "Perhaps that's it.\~ Yes.\~ Now, go to sleep."
\par "You haven't told me why you're doing this."
\par "I want your world to understand something:\~ That an innocent from your people can die just as other innocents have died."
\par The boy went pale, his mouth in a rigid grimace.\~ He whispered:\~ "You're going to kill me."
\par "Perhaps not," Katsuk lied.\~ "You must remember that the gift of words is the gift of illusion."
\par "But you said. . . ."
\par "I say this to you, Hoquat:\~ Your world will feel my message in its balls!\~ If you do as I tell you, all will go well with you."
\par "You're lying!"
\par Anger and shame tore at Katsuk.\~ "Shut up!" he shouted.
\par "You are!\~ You're lying -- you're lying."\~ The boy was sobbing now.
\par "Shut up or I'll kill you right now," Katsuk growled.
\par The sobs were choked off, but the wide-open eyes continued to stare up at him.
\par Katsuk found his anger gone.\~ Only shame remained.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 I did lie.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par He realized how undignified he had become.\~ To allow his own emotion such wild expression!\~ He felt shattered, seduced into the word ways of the hoquat, isolated by words, miserable and lonely.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 What men gave me this misery? }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 he wondered.
\par Barren sorrow permeated him.\~ He sighed.\~ Soul Catcher gave him no choice.\~ The decision had been made.\~ There could be no reprieve.\~ But the boy had learned to detect lies.
\par Speaking as reasonably as he could, Katsuk said:\~ "You need sleep."
\par "How can I sleep when you're going to kill me?"
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 A reasonable question, }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Katsuk thought.
\par He said:\~ "I will not kill you while you sleep."
\par "I don't believe you."
\par "I swear it by my spirits, by the name I gave you, by my own name."
\par "Why should I believe that crazy stuff about spirits?"
\par Katsuk pulled the knife partly from its sheath, said:\~ "Close your eyes and you live."
\par The boy's eyes blinked shut, snapped open.
\par Katsuk found this vaguely amusing but wondered how he could convince Hoquat.\~ Every word scattered what it touched.
\par He asked:\~ "If I go outside, will you sleep?"
\par "I'll try."
\par "I will go outside then."
\par "My hands hurt."
\par Katsuk took a deep breath of resignation, bent to examine the bindings.\~ They were tight but did not completely shut off circulation.\~ He released the knots, chafed the boy's wrists.\~
 Presently, he restored the bindings, added a slip noose to each arm above the elbows.
\par He said:\~ "If you struggle to escape now, these new knots will pull tight and shut off the circulation of blood to your arms.\~ If that happens, I will not help you.\~ I'll just let your arms drop off."
\par "Will you go outside now?"
\par "Yes."
\par "Are you going to eat?"
\par "No."
\par "I'm hungry."
\par "We will eat when you waken."
\par "What will we eat?"
\par "There are many things to eat here:\~ roots, grubs. . . ."
\par "You'll stay outside?"
\par "Yes.\~ Go to sleep.\~ We face a long night.\~ You will have to keep up with me then.\~ If you cannot keep up, I will }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 be }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
forced to kill you."
\par "Why're you doing this?"
\par "I told you."
\par "No, you didn't."
\par "Shut up and go to sleep."
\par "I'll wake up if you come back."
\par Katsuk could not suppress a grin.\~ "Good.\~ I know what to do when I want to awaken you."
\par He stood up, went down to the spring pool, pushed his face into the water.\~ It felt cold and fresh against his skin.\~ He squatted back on his heels, allowed his senses to test the silences of this place.\~ 
When he was sure of his surroundings, he made his way out to the edge of the trees where the shale slope began.\~ He sat there for a time, quiet as a grouse crouching in its own shadow.\~ He could see the trail his people had beaten down for centuries.\~ 
It skirted the trees far down below the slide.\~ The trail remained quite visible from this height, although forest and bracken had reclaimed it.
\par He told himself:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 I must be strong now.\~ My people have need of me.\~ Our trails are eaten by the forest.\~ Our children are cursed and slaughtered.\~ 
Our old men do not speak to us anymore in words we can understand.\~ We have withstood evil heaped upon evil but we are dying.\~ We are landless in our own land.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par Quietly, to himself, Katsuk began singing the names of his dead:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Janiktaht . . . Kipskiltch. . . .\~ }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
As he sang, he thought how all of the past had been woven into the spirit of his people's songs and now the songs, too, were dying.
\par A black bear came out of the trees far below him, skirted the slide, and went up the fireweed slope eating kinnikinnick.\~ It gave the shale a wide berth.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 We need not hurry here, }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Katsuk thought.
\par Presently, he crept under the wide skirt of a fat spruce, deep into the shadows of the low boughs.\~ He lay down facing the shale slope and prepared to sleep with the smell of the forest floor in his nostrils.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Soon, }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 he thought, }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
