\s15\ql \li0\ri0\sb100\sa100\sbauto1\saauto1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\ipgp1 \fs24\lang1049\langfe1049\cgrid\langnp1049\langfenp1049 {\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 \page David awakened.

\par For a moment his only awareness was of hunger cramps and the dry, hot thirst rasping his throat.\~ Then he felt the thongs around his wrists and arms.\~ He experienced surprise that he had slept.\~ His eyes felt rough and heavy.\~ 
Katsuk's warning against fighting the thongs came back to him.\~ The cave light was a green grayness.\~ He had scattered the cushioning moss.\~ Coldness from the rock beneath him chilled his flesh.\~ A moment of shivering overcame him.\~ Whe
n it passed, his gaze went up the thong to the loop secured around the rock spur.\~ It was much too high.
\par Where was that crazy Katsuk?
\par David struggled to a sitting position.\~ As he moved, he heard a helicopter pass across the rock slope directly opposite the cave's mouth.
\par He recognized the sound immediately and hope surged through him.\~ Nothing else made quite that sound:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Helicopter!}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par David held his breath.\~ He remembered the handkerchief he had dropped below the slide.\~ He had carried the handkerchief for miles during the nightmare journey, wondering where to drop it.\~ 
The handkerchief carried his monogrammed initials -- a distinctive }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 DMM.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par He had wormed the handkerchief from his pocket soon after thinking about it, wadded the cloth into a ball, and held it -- waiting . . . waiting.\~ There had been no sense dropping it too soon.\~
 Katsuk had led them up and down streams, confusing their trail.\~ David had thought of tearing the cloth into bits, dropping the pieces like a paper chase, but the monogram occupied only one corner and he had felt certain Katsuk would hear cloth ripping.

\par At the rock slope, David had been moved as much by fatigue and desperation as any other motive.\~ Katsuk was sure to hide them during daylight.\~ The ground below the slope was open to the sky.\~ No trail crossed that area.\~
 A handkerchief in an unusual place }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 could }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 attract attention.\~ 
And Katsuk had been so intent on the slide, so confident, he had not been watching his back trail.
\par Surely, the men in the helicopter out there now had seen the handkerchief.
\par Again, the noisy racket of rotors swept across the mouth of the notch and its concealed cave.\~ What were they doing?\~ Would they land?
\par David wished he could see the slope.\~ Where was that crazy Katsuk?\~ Had he been seen?\~ David's throat burned with thirst.\~ Again, the helicopter passed the notch.\~ David strained to hear any telltale variation in sound.\~ Was rescue at hand?
\par He thought of the long night's march, the fears which had blocked his thoughts, the dark paths full of root stumbles.\~ Hunger and terror cramped him now, doubled him over.\~ He stared down at the cave's rock floor.\~ 
The bear smell of the place came thickly into his nostrils.
\par Again, the machine sound flooded the cave.
\par David tried to recall the appearance of the slope.\~ Was there a place for a helicopter to land?\~ 
He had been so tired when they had emerged from the trees, so thirsty and hungry, so filled with desperation about where to leave the telltale handkerchief, he had not really seen the area.\~ The blind feelings of the 
night with its stars cold and staring clogged his memory.\~ He recalled only the confused surge of bird cries at dawn, falling upon senses amplified by hunger and thirst.
\par What were they doing in that helicopter?\~ Where was Katsuk?
\par David tried to recall riding in a helicopter.\~ He had traveled with his parents to and from airports in helicopters.\~ That sound had to be a helicopter.\~
 But he had never paid much attention to what landing place a helicopter required, except to know it could land on a small space.\~ Could it land on a slope?\~ He didn't know.
\par Perhaps the rockslide kept the machine from landing.\~ Katsuk had warned about that danger.\~ Maybe Katsuk had a gun now.\~ he could have hidden one here and recovered it.\~ He could be out there waiting to shoot down the helicopter.
\par David shook his head from side to side in desperation.
\par He thought of shouting.\~ No one in the helicopter would hear him above that engine noise.\~ And Katsuk had warned that death would follow any outcry.
\par David recalled his own knife in its sheath at Katsuk's waist -- the Russell knife from Canada.\~ He imagined that knife being pulled from its sheath by Katsuk's dark hand -- one hard thrust --
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 He'll kill me sure if I shout.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par The clatter of the machine circling in and out of the clearing around the rockslide confused David.\~ The cave and its masking trees baffled the sound.\~
 He could not tell when the helicopter flew low into the slope or when it hovered above the cliff -- only that it was out there, louder sometimes than at other times.\~ Where was Katsuk?
\par David's teeth chattered with cold and terror.\~ Hunger and thirst chopped time into uneven bits.\~ The dusty yellow light outside the cave told him nothing.\~ No matter how hard 
he listened, straining to identify what was happening, he could not interpret the sounds into meaning.
\par There was only the single fact of the helicopter.\~ The sound of it filled the cave once more.\~ This time it came as an oddly distorted noise building slowly into a rumbling roar louder than thunder.\~ The cave trembled around him.
\par Had they crashed?
\par He held his breath as the terrifying noise went on and on and on . . . louder, louder.\~ It built to a climax, subsided.\~ The noise of a raven flock became audible.\~ The helicopter had faded to a distant background throbbing.
\par He could still hear the machine, though.\~ The rotors' }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 beat-beat-beat }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
mingled with drifts of cold green light within the cave to dominate David's awareness.\~ He swallowed dry terror, listened with an intensity which began in the middle of his back.\~ The sound of the helicopter faded . . . faded . . . vanished.\~
 He heard ravens calling and the dull clap of their wings.
\par The arch of the cave mouth was filled by Katsuk's black silhouette, its edges blurred by dusty light from outside.\~ Katsuk advanced without a word, removed the thongs from the rock, untied the boy's wrists and arms.
\par David wondered:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Why doesn't he say something?\~ What happened out there?}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par Katsuk felt David's hip pocket.
\par David thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 The handkerchief!\~ }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 He tried to swallow, stared at his captor, begging for a clue to what was happening.

\par "That was very clever," Katsuk said, his voice conversational.\~ He began massaging the boy's wrists.\~ "Very, very clever; so very clever."
\par The sound of Katsuk speaking low, a voice like smoke in the cave, filled David with more fear than if the man had betrayed rage.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 If he calls me Hoquat, }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 David thought, }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
I must remember to answer and not anger him.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par Katsuk released David's wrists, sat down facing the boy.\~ He said:\~ "You will want to know what happened.\~ I will tell it."
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 I am Hoquat, }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 David reminded himself.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
I must keep him calm.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par David watched Katsuk's lips, eyes, listened for any change of tone, any sign of emotion.\~ Words came slow cadence from Katsuk's mouth:\~ "Raven . . . giant bird . . . devil machine. . . ."
\par The words carried odd half-meanings.\~ David felt he was hearing some fanciful story, not about a helicopter but about a giant bird called Raven and Raven's victory over evil.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "You know, when Raven was young, he was the father of my people.\~ He brought us the sun and the moon and the stars.\~ He brought us fire.\~ He was white then, like you, but fire smoke blackened his feathers.\~ 
It was that Raven who came back today and hid me from your devil machine -- black Raven.\~ He saved me.\~ Do you understand?"
\par David trembled, unable to comprehend or to answer.
\par Katsuk's eyes reflected cobalt glints in the cave's half-light.\~ The sunlight pouring in the entrance behind him put a honey glow on his skin, made him appear larger.
\par "Why are you trembling?" Katsuk asked.
\par "I . . . I'm cold."
\par "Are you hungry?"
\par "Y-yes."
\par "Then I will teach you how to live in my land.\~ Many things are provided here to sustain us -- roots, sweet ants, fat grubs, flowers, bulbs, leaves.\~ You will learn these things and become a man of the woods."
\par "A w-woodsman?"
\par Katsuk shook his head from side to side.\~ "A man of the woods.\~ That is much different.\~ You are sly and have a devil in you.\~ These make the man of the woods."
\par The words made no sense to David, but he nodded.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "Raven said to me we can travel by daylight.\~ We will go now because the hoquat will be sending men on foot.\~ They will come to this place because of your sly handkerchief."
\par David ran his tongue over his lips.\~ "Where are we going?"
\par "Far into the mountains.\~ We will find the valley of peace, perhaps, where my ancestors put all the fresh water once."
\par David thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 He's crazy, pure crazy.\~ }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 And he said:\~ "I'm thirsty."
\par "You can drink from the spring.\~ Stand up now."
\par David obeyed, wondered if the thongs would be tied on his wrists.\~ His side hurt where he had slept on the rock floor of the cave.\~ He looked at the light flaring outside.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
Travel by daylight . . . with a helicopter out there somewhere?}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par Was pursuit close on their heels?\~ Was crazy Katsuk running in daylight because searchers were near?
\par Katsuk said:\~ "You think your friends will fly to us in their devil machine and rescue you."
\par David stared at the cave floor.
\par Katsuk chuckled.\~ "What is your name?"
\par "Hoquat."\~ Without looking up.
\par "Very good.\~ But your friends will not see us, Hoquat."
\par David looked up into staring dark eyes.\~ "Why not?"
\par Katsuk nodded at the cave mouth.\~ "Raven spoke to me out there.\~ He told me he will conceal us from all searchers in the sky.\~ I will not even bind you.\~ Raven will keep you from running away.\~ 
If you try to escape, Raven will show me how to kill you.\~ Do you understand me, Hoquat?"
\par "Y-yes.\~ I won't try to escape."
\par Katsuk smiled pleasantly.\~ "That is what Raven told me."
\par }\pard \s15\qc \li0\ri0\sb100\sa100\sbauto1\saauto1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\ipgp1 {\insrsid8201588 * * *
