\s15\ql \li0\ri0\sb100\sa100\sbauto1\saauto1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\ipgp1 \fs24\lang1049\langfe1049\cgrid\langnp1049\langfenp1049 {\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 \page 
Katsuk had led him into solid shadows under trees, and David prayed now that the aircraft would come only when they were in a clearing or on a trail not shielded by trees.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Crazy Indian!}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par Katsuk felt the pressure of the boy's thoughts, but he knew the two figures in this forest gloom were not people.\~ No people passed this way.\~ They were primal elements who snagged their essence upon bits of time like animal fur caught on thorns.\~ 
His own thoughts went as wind through grass, moving this world only after they had passed.\~ And when they had passed, everything behind them resolved itself into silence, almost-but-not-quite the way it had been before their intrusion.
\par Yet -- something changed.
\par They changed something essential that could be felt on the farthest star.
\par Once Katsuk stopped, faced the boy, and said:
\par "Therefore the flight shall perish from the swift, and the strong shall not strengthen his force, neither shall the mighty deliver himself.\~ That's what it says in your hoquat book.\~ It says he that is courag
eous among the mighty shall flee away naked in the day.\~ You hoquat had some wise men once, but you never listened."
\par Another time, they rested and drank at a spring that bubbled from a ledge.\~ A green river roared in its chasm below them.\~ High clouds rippled the sky and there were hill shadows on gray rocks across the river.
\par Katsuk pointed down to the river.\~ "Look."
\par David whirled, stared down, and in the quick rhythm of light flung by the river into the canyon's gloom he saw a brown deer swimming, its head thrusting at the far shore.\~ The light and sound and animal movement roaring together dazzled his mind.
\par There was a dark chill in the wind, and as they left the spring David sensed the quick silence of the forest birds.\~ More clouds had accumulated.\~ A deerfly crouched on his arm.\~ He watched it pause and take flight.\~
 He had long since given up hope that Katsuk would produce food from this wilderness.\~ It had been talk, just talk -- all those words about food in this place.\~ Katsuk had said it himself:\~ Words fooled you.
\par David's eyes was caught by the venturesome racing of a squirrel's feet along a high limb.\~ He wondered only if the creature could be caught and eaten.
\par The day wore on.\~ Sometimes Katsuk talked about himself and his people, fanciful stories indistinguishable from reality.\~ They moved through damp woods, through sunlit clearings, beneath clouds, beneath dripping leaves.\~ 
Always, there was the sound of their own footsteps.
\par David forgot about his hunger in the presence of great weariness.\~ Where were they going?\~ Why were there no more aircraft?
\par Katsuk did not think of a destination, saying, "Now we are here, and we will go there."\~ He felt himself changing, sensed the ancient instincts taking over.\~ He sensed blank places growing in his memory
, things he no longer knew in the ways this hoquat world accepted.
\par Where would the changes in him lead?
\par The answer unfolded in his mind, the spirits revealing their wisdom:\~ The workings of his brain would go through a deep metamorphosis until, at last, his mind lay like a drunk within his driven self.\~ He would be Soul Catcher entirely.
\par There was a spring shadowed by a giant cotton-wood.\~ Deer tracks led up to it and all around.\~ Katsuk stopped and they drank.\~ The boy splashed his face and collar.
\par Katsuk watched him, thinking:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 How powerful, this young human, how strange, drinking from that spring with his hands.\~ What would his people think of such a lad in such a pose?}{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par There was a new grace in things the boy did.\~ He was fitting himself into this life.\~ When it was time for silence, he was silent.\~ When it was time to drink, he drank.\~ Hunger came upon him in its proper order.\~
 The spirit of the wilderness had seeped into him, beginning to say that it was right for such a one to be here.\~ The rightness of it had not yet become complete, though.\~ This was still a hoquat lad.\~
 The cells of his flesh whispered rebellion and rejection of the earth around him.\~ At any moment he might strike out and become once more the total alien to this place.\~ The thing lay in delicate balance.
\par Katsuk imagined himself then as a person who adjusted that balance.\~ The boy must not demand food before its time.\~ Thirst must be quenched only in the rhythm of thirst.\~ The shattering intrusion of a voice must be prevented by willing
 it not to happen.
\par Bees weighted with pollen were working in fireweed on the slope below the spring.\~ Katsuk thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 They watch us.\~ They are the spirit eyes from which we never escape.}{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par He stared through leaf-tattered light at the working creatures.\~ They were fitted into the orderliness of this place.\~ They were not many creatures, but one single organism.\~ They were Bee, the spirit messenger who had brought him here.
\par The boy finished drinking at the spring, sat back on his heels, watchful, waiting.
\par For a glimmering instant, something in the set of the boy's head opened for Katsuk a glimpse of the man who had fathered this human.\~ The adult peered out of youthful eyes, weighing, judging, planning.
\par Momentarily, it unnerved Katsuk to think of that man-and-father here.\~ The father was no innocent.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 He }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
would have all of the hoquat vices.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 He }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
would have the powers, evil and good, which had given the hoquat dominion over the primitive world.\~ That one must be kept in the background, suppressed.
\par How could it be done?\~ The boy's flesh could not be separated from that which gave it life.\~ A spirit power must be invoked here.\~ Which spirit power?\~ How?\~ Could the man-father be driven away with his own guilt?
\par Katsuk thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 My father should come to help me now.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par He tried to call up a vision of his father, but no face came, not even a voice.
\par Katsuk felt the seeds of panic.
\par There had been a father.\~ The man had existed.\~ He was back there walking the beaches, fishing, breeding two children.\~ But he had taken the path of drink and inward rage and a death in the water.\~ Were the hoquat to blame for that?
\par Where was his face, his voice?\~ He was Hobuhet, the Riverman, whose people had lived on this land for twice a thousand years.\~ He had fathered a son.
\par And Katsuk thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 But I am no longer Charles Hobuhet.\~ I am Katsuk.\~ Bee is my father.\~ I have been called to do a terrible thing.\~ The spirit I must call upon is Soul Catcher.}{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par Silently, he prayed then, and saw at once how the boy's eyelids blinked, how his attention wandered.\~ No power stood against Soul Catcher in this wilderness.\~ Once more, Katsuk felt calm.\~ The greatest of the spirits could not be doubted.\~
 The hoquat father had been driven back into the flesh.\~ Only the Innocent remained.
\par Katsuk arose and strode off along the slope, hearing the boy follow.\~ There had been no need for words of command.\~ Soul Catcher had created a wake in the air which drew the boy into it as though he were caught on a tow line.
\par Now, Katsuk left the game trail he had been following and struck off through moss-draped hemlocks.\~ There was a granite ledge up above them somewhere hemming in the river valley.\~ 
Without ordering his feet to seek that place, Katsuk knew he could find it.
\par He came on the first outcroppings within the hour and moved out of the trees, climbing a slope of stunted huckleberry bushes toward rock shade.\~ The boy followed, panting, pulling himself up by the bushes as he saw Katsuk doing.\~ 
They emerged presently on a bald rock and there was the river valley spread out southward with sweet grass and elk grazing in a meadow.
\par A string of fat quail stuttered through sun-splashed shadows below him, catching Katsuk's attention.\~ The quail reminded him of a hunger which he knew his body would feel if it were time for that sensation.\~ 
But he sensed no hunger, knowing by this that his flesh had accommodated itself to primitive ways.
\par The boy had sprawled out on sun-warmed rock.\~ Katsuk wondered if Hoquat felt hunger or denied it.\~ The lad also was accommodating to primitive ways.\~ But how was he doing it?\~ 
Was he immersed so deeply in each moment that only the needs of the moment called out to his senses?\~ The climb had tired him and thus he rested.\~ That was the correct way.\~ But what else had changed in the hoquat flesh?
\par Carefully, Katsuk studied his captive.\~ Perspiration had left damp darkness in the hair at the boy's neck.\~ Stains of brown dirt marked the legs of his trousers.\~ Streaks of mud were drying on his canvas shoes.
\par Katsuk smelled the boy's sweat, a youthful, musky sweetness in it which called up memories of school locker rooms.\~ He thought:
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 It is a fact that the earth which marks us on the surface also leaves its traces within us.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par There would come a moment when the boy was tied so firmly to this wilderness that he could not escape it.\~ If the link were forged in the right way, innocence maintained, there would be a power in it to challenge any spirit.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 I was marked by his world; now he is marked by mine.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par This had become a contest on two levels -- the straightforward capture of a victim and the victim's desire to escape, but beneath that a wrestling of spirits.\~ The signs of that other contest were all around.
\par Katsuk looked out across the valley.\~ There was an old forest on the far slope, fire dead, burned silver hacking the green background into brittle shapes.
\par The boy turned onto his back, threw a hand across his eyes.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "We will go now."
\par "Can't we wait just a minute?"\~ Without removing the hand from his eyes.
\par Katsuk chuckled.\~ "You think I don't know what you've been doing?"
\par The boy took the hand away, looked up at Katsuk.\~ "What do you. . . ."
\par "You slow down when we're crossing a meadow.\~ You trip when we ford the river, then you want me to build a fire.\~ You think I don't know why you complained when we left the elk trail?"
\par Blood suffused the boy's cheeks.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "Look where we are now, eh?"\~ He pointed skyward.\~ "Wide open to searching devil machines, huh?\~ Or men could see us from the valley.\~ They could identify us with binoculars."
\par The boy glared at him.\~ "Why do you say }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 devil machines }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 instead of helicopters?\~ You know what they are."
\par "True, I know what you think they are.\~ But different people see things differently."
\par David turned away.\~ He felt stubborn determination to prolong this moment in the open.\~ Hunger and fatigue helped him now.\~ They sapped his physical strength but fed his rage.
\par Abruptly, Katsuk laughed, sat down beside him.
\par "Very well, Hoquat.\~ I will demonstrate Raven's power.\~ We will rest here while it's warm.\~ Stare at the sky all you wish.\~ Raven will hide us even if a devil machine flies directly over us."
\par David thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 He really believes that!}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par Katsuk rolled onto his side, studied his captive.\~ How strange that Hoquat didn't understand about Tamanawis.\~ The boy would wait and wait, hoping, praying.\~ But Raven had spoken.
\par The rock felt warm and soothing beneath him.\~ Katsuk rolled onto his back, glanced around.\~ A quaking aspen grew from the sunward side of their aerie.\~ The quickness of the bright sun pulsing on the aspen's leaves made him think of Hoquat's life.

\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Yes, Hoquat is like that:\~ trembling in every wind, now glittering bright, now shadowy, now innocent, now evil.\~ He is the perfect Hoquat for me.}{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par The boy said:\~ "You don't really believe that raven stuff."
\par Katsuk spoke softly:\~ "You will see."
\par "A guy at camp said you went to the university.\~ They must teach you at the university how stupid that stuff is."
\par "Yes, I went to the hoquat university.\~ They teach ignorance there.\~ I could not learn ignorance, although everyone was studying it.\~ Maybe I'm too stupid."
\par Katsuk grinned at the sky, his gaze aimlessly following an osprey which soared and circled high above them.
\par David watched his captor covertly, thinking how the man was like a big cat he'd seen at the San Francisco zoo -- supine on the rock, reclining at ease, the tawny skin dulled by an overlay of dust, eyes blinking, flaring, blinking.
\par "Katsuk?"
\par "Yes, Hoquat."
\par "They're going to catch you and kill you."
\par "Only if Raven permits it."
\par "You were probably so stupid they wouldn't let you stay at the university!"
\par "Haven't I admitted it?"
\par "What do you know about anything?"
\par Katsuk heard the rage and fear in the boy's voice, wondered what kind of a son this one had been.\~ It was easy to think of that stage in the boy's life as past -- all done.\~ This one would never live to a ripe and wrinkled fulfillment.\~ 
He had accepted too many lies, this one.\~ Even without a Katsuk he would never have made it to a rich old time of quiet.
\par "You don't know anything!" the boy pressed.
\par Katsuk shrugged himself into a new position, selected a stem of grass growing from a crack in the rock.\~ He slipped the grass free of its sheath, began to chew the sweet juices.
\par David tasted the sourness at the back of his throat, muttered:\~ "You're just stupid!"
\par Slowly, Katsuk turned his head, studied the boy.\~ "In this place, Hoquat, I am the professor and you are the stupid."
\par The boy rolled away, stared into the sky.
\par "Look up there all you wish," Katsuk said.\~ "Raven hides us from searchers."\~ He extracted another grassblade from its green sheath, chewed it.
\par "Professor!" the boy sneered.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "And you are slow to learn.\~ You are hungry, yet there is food all around us."
\par The young eyes jerked toward the grass in Katsuk's mouth.
\par "Yes, this grass.\~ It has much sugar in it.\~ Back when we crossed the river, you saw me take the roots of those reeds, wash them, and chew them.\~ You saw me eat those fat grubs, but you only wondered out loud how we could catch fish."
\par David felt the words burn into his consciousness.\~ Grass grew from the rock near his head.\~ He yanked a stem.\~ It came up by its roots.
\par Katsuk chuckled, selected a supple young shoot, showed how to draw out the tender stem -- slowly, firmly -- without disturbing the roots.
\par David chewed the grass, experimentally at first.\~ Finding it sweet, he ground the stem in his teeth.\~ Hunger knotted his stomach.\~ He pulled another stem, another. . . .
\par Katsuk interrupted:\~ "You've learned one lesson.\~ Come.\~ We will go now."
\par "You're afraid your raven can't hide us."
\par "You want a conclusive scientific test, eh?\~ Very well, just stay where you are."
\par Katsuk turned away, cocked his head to one side, listening.
\par The pose primed David's senses.\~ He felt the sound of an engine in the air, realized Katsuk must have been hearing it for some time.\~ So that was why he'd wanted to go!
\par Katsuk said:\~ "You hear it?"
\par David held his breath.\~ The sound grew louder.\~ He felt his heart beating wildly.
\par Katsuk lay back without moving.
\par David thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 If I jump up and wave, he'll kill me.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par Katsuk closed his eyes.\~ He felt sheet lightning in his brain, an inner sky filled with fire.\~ This was an ultimate test.\~ He prayed for the inner sense of power.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 This is Katsuk}{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588  -- The sound of the helicopter weighed upon his senses.
\par David stared southwest across the aspen which shaded their rock.\~ The sound was coming from there.\~ It grew louder . . . louder.
\par Katsuk lay motionless, with his eyes closed.
\par David wanted to shout:\~ "Run!"\~ It was insane.\~ But Katsuk would be caught if he stayed there.\~ Why didn't he get up and run into the trees?
\par A fit of trembling overcame David.
\par Movement flickered in the sky above the aspen.
\par David stared, frozen.
\par The helicopter was high but in plain sight.\~ His gaze followed its passage:\~ a big helicopter flying through a patch of blue sky between clouds.\~ It flew from right to left in the open sky perhaps a mile away.\~ 
An occupant would only have to glance this way to see two figures on the high rock escarpment.
\par The big machine crossed the far ridge of the river valley.\~ High trees there gradually concealed it.\~ The sound diminished.
\par As it disappeared, a single raven flew over the rock where David lay, then another, another --
\par The birds flew silently, intent upon some private destination.
\par Katsuk opened his eyes in time to see the last of them.\~ The sound of the helicopter was gone.\~ He looked at the boy.\~ "You did not try to attract their attention.\~ Why?\~ I would not have stopped you."
\par David's glance flicked across the knife at Katsuk's waist.\~ "Yes, you would."
\par "I would not."
\par David sensed an impulse in the words, a confidence that spoke of truth.\~ He reacted with bitter frustration.\~ It made him want to run and cry.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "Raven hides us."
\par David thought of the birds which had flown overhead.\~ They had arrived after the helicopter was gone.\~ It made no real sense to him, but David felt the flight of birds had been a signal.\~ 
He had the eerie sensation that the birds had spoken to Katsuk in some private way.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "I don't have to kill you while Raven protects.\~ Without Raven's protection . . . well. . . ."
\par David whirled away.\~ Tears stung his eyes.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 I should've jumped up and waved!\~ I should've tried!}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par In one supple motion, Katsuk arose, said:\~ "We go now."
\par Without a backward glance to see if the boy followed, Katsuk crossed the open rock, plunged into the trees on the next slope.\~ He sensed rain in that southwest wind.\~ Tonight it would rain.
\par }\pard \s15\qc \li0\ri0\sb100\sa100\sbauto1\saauto1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\ipgp1 {\insrsid8201588 * * *
