\s15\ql \li0\ri0\sb100\sa100\sbauto1\saauto1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\ipgp1 \fs24\lang1049\langfe1049\cgrid\langnp1049\langfenp1049 {\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 \page 
David fingered the two small pebbles in his pocket -- one for each day.\~ The second day with this madman.\~ They had slept and dozed through the night beneath a ledge which sheltered them from the rain.\~ Katsuk had
 refused to build a fire, but he had gone alone into the forest and returned with food:\~ a gray mush in a bark bowl.\~ David had wolfed it, savoring an acrid sweetness.\~
 Katsuk had explained then that it was lily roots chopped with grubs and sweet red ants.
\par At the look of revulsion on David's face, Katsuk had laughed, said:\~ "Squeamishness can kill you out here as fast as anything else.\~ That is good food.\~ It has everything in it that you need."
\par The laughter had silenced David's objections more than any other argument.\~ He had eaten the gray mush again as dawn glared over the trees.
\par He had been following Katsuk two hours this morning before his clothes dried.
\par There were hemlocks overhead now.\~ Ancient blaze marks formed pitch-ringed scars on some of the tree trunks.\~ Katsuk had recognized the marks and explained them:\~ This was a way his ancestors had traveled.\~ 
Ferns and moss lay in a tangled miniature wilderness under the trees, obscuring the ancient track, but Katsuk said this was the way.
\par The sky darkened.\~ David wondered if it was going to rain again.
\par Up ahead, Katsuk paused, studied his surroundings.\~ He turned, watched the boy plunging along behind -- over mossy logs, around great clumps of fern.
\par Katsuk stared down the slope ahead of him.\~ The ancient elk trail his people had used ran somewhere down there.\~ He would cross it soon and follow the path of his wild brethren.
\par The boy came up to him, stood panting.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "Stay closer to me."
\par He set out once more, skirted a mossy log, noted beneath it a tiny dewed spiderweb.\~ All around him lay a forest of mossy limbs -- every limb draped with moss like green wool hung out to dry.\~ 
The light, now bright and now dull as clouds concealed the sun, alternately flattened the colors and then filled the world with green jeweled glowing.\~ 
At one passage of muted green, the sun suddenly emerged and sent a rope of light plunging through the trees to the forest floor.
\par Katsuk walked through the light, then ducked under dark boughs.\~ He heard limbs catching at the boy behind him, scratching, slithering.
\par Beyond the dark passage, Katsuk stopped, reached out a hand, and caught the boy from stepping past.\~ The trail was directly in front of them about two feet down a steep bank.\~ It sloped down to the left.\~ Tracks of hiking boots marked the soft earth.

\par David saw the tension in Katsuk, listened for the sound of the hikers.\~ The tracks appeared fresh.\~ Water trickled down the trail but had not yet filled the tracks.
\par Katsuk turned, glanced at the boy, motioned flatly with one hand -- back up the way they had come.
\par David shook his head.\~ "What?"
\par Katsuk stared up the hill behind them, said:\~ "That big log we came over.\~ Go back there and hide behind it.\~ If I hear or see any sign of your presence, I will kill you."
\par David stepped backward, turned, and climbed back to the log.\~ It was a cedar, its bark hidden beneath moss, but live limbs climbed skyward along its length.\~ Katsuk had pointed out another such fallen tree, calling it a nurse log.\~ 
The limbs would be trees some day.\~ David climbed back over the nurse log.
\par He sank to his heels there, stared through the shadows.\~ His eyes looked for color, for movement.\~ In his own silence, he grew aware of the constant sound of water dripping all around.\~ He felt the dampness of this place.\~
 His feet were sopping and his trousers were dark with water almost to the waist.\~ It was cold.
\par Katsuk stepped down to the trail, turned left in the direction of the hikers' tracks.\~ He glided down the trail, moving with a wraith quality -- brown skin, the white loincloth tugging at David's gaze.
\par The trail switched back to the right.\~ Katsuk turned with it.\~ Only his head and shoulders remained visible to the watching boy.
\par Abruptly, far down the hillside David saw color and movement -- a group of hikers.\~ As though vision opened the air to sound, he heard their voices then:\~ no distinguishable words, but sudden laughter and a shout.
\par David sank farther down behind the log, peered out between a tangle of dead limbs.\~ As he did it, he wondered:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Why am I hiding?\~ 
Why don't I sneak around Katsuk and get to those hikers?\~ They'd protect me from him.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par But he sensed his own destruction in any movement.\~ Part of Katsuk remained focused on his captive, some inner sense.\~ There might even be ravens around.
\par David crouched, tense and quivering.
\par Katsuk had stopped, head and shoulders visible above the trail embankment.\~ He stared up toward David, then looked up the trail.
\par David heard noise up the trail then, tried to swallow in a dry throat.\~ More hikers?
\par He thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 I could shout.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par But he knew any outcry would bring Katsuk and the knife.
\par Slogging, heavy footsteps became audible.
\par A bearded young man came down the trail.\~ A green pack rode high on his shoulders.\~ His long hair was bound at the forehead by a red bandanna.\~ It gave him a curiously aboriginal look.\~
 The hiker glanced neither right nor left but kept his attention on the trail.\~ He walked with a stiff, heel-first stride that jarred the ground.
\par David felt giddy with fear.\~ He no longer could see Katsuk but knew the man lay in wait down there somewhere.\~ He would be watching the hiker from some hidden spot below.
\par David thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 All I have to do is stand up and shout.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par The other hikers might not hear it, but this one would.\~ He was just passing David's hiding place.\~ The other hikers were a long way down there though.\~ There was a stream down in that canyon.\~ Its noise would hide any sound from up here.
\par David thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Katsuk would kill this guy . . . and then me.\~ He told me what he'd do . . . and he meant it.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par The bearded hiker was at the switchback.\~ He would see Katsuk momentarily, or pass right by without noticing anything.
\par What was Katsuk doing?
\par For several minutes, Katsuk had felt a test of purpose building to a climax.\~ In that dark passage before he had reached the trail, he had felt an odd fear that he would find his secret name carved some place -- on a tree or stump or log.
\par At the few open places, he had stared up at the sky -- now gray, now bright as blue-green glass.\~ It was a crystal without form, but ready to take any shape.\~ Perhaps his name would be written there.
\par A bulbous gray quinine canker on an old stump had filled him with foreboding.\~ He had thought of Hoquat following him like a pet on a leash.\~ Then, wonderingly:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Soul Catcher has
 given me power over Raven, but that is not enough.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par He wondered if there were any }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 thing }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 in these mountains with the power to set his universe in perfect order once more.\~ 
A vision of Janiktaht filled his mind:\~ a head with sand on its cheeks, a head turned to seaweed shadows, the face broken upon its imperfections.\~ The ghost of Janiktaht could not set things right.
\par Now he heard the voices and laughter of the hikers below and thought it was people taunting him.\~ He heard the lone straggler coming.
\par The forest was a dull green-gray world suddenly, lidded by a lead sky.\~ 
The wind had gone down under the trees, and in that new silence of birds and a storm building, Katsuk thought he heard his own heart beating only when he moved, that it stopped when he stopped.
\par Hatred formed in him then.\~ What right had these hoquat to play in his forest?\~ He felt all the defeats of his people.\~ Their sobs and oaths and lamenting echoed within him, a swarm of unavenged shadows.
\par The bearded hiker came around the switchback, his head down, the many signs of fatigue in his stride.\~ The pack was too heavy, of course, filled with things he did not need here.
\par With a dull shock, Katsuk realized he had seen that bearded face before -- on the university campus.\~ He could put no name to the face, only a vague recognition that this was a student he had seen.\~ It bothered him that he could not name the face.

\par In that instant, the hiker saw Katsuk crouched on the trail and jarred to a stop.
\par "Wha. . . ."\~ The young man shook his head, then:
\par "Hey, It's Charlie the Chief!\~ Hey, man, What're y' doing out here in that getup?\~ You playing Indians and settlers?"
\par Katsuk straightened, thinking:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 The fool doesn't know.\~ Of course he doesn't.\~ He's been in my forest without a radio.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 

\par The hiker said:\~ "I'm Vince Debay, remember?\~ We were in that Anthro Three-hundred class together."
\par Katsuk said:\~ "Hello, Vince."
\par Vince leaned his pack against the trail's uphill embankment, took a deep breath.\~ His face betrayed the questions in his mind.\~ He could not help but recognize the strangeness of this encounter.\~ 
He might recognize the face, but he must know this was not the same Charlie the Chief of that Anthro 300 class.\~ He must know it!\~ Katsuk felt hate covering his face with a stale mask as dry and wrinkled as a discarded snakeskin.\~ 
Surely, Vince could see it.
\par Vince said:\~ "Man, am I tired.\~ We've been all morning coming from the Kimta.\~ We were hoping to make it to Finley Shelter by tonight, but it doesn't look like we're going to make it."\~ He waved a hand.\~
 "Hey, I was just joking, you know -- about Indians and settlers.\~ No offense."
\par Katsuk nodded.
\par "You see the other guys?" Vince asked.
\par Katsuk shook his head.
\par Vince said:\~ "Why the loincloth bit, man?\~ Aren't you cold?"
\par "No."
\par "I stopped to blow a little grass.\~ The other guys must be almost to the bottom by now."\~ He peered around Katsuk.\~ "I think I hear them.\~ Hey, guys!"\~ The last came out in a shout.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "They can't hear you.\~ They're too close to the river."
\par "I guess you're right."
\par Katsuk thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 I must kill him without anger, an act of irony.\~ I must cut a malignant and venomous thing from my forest.\~ It will be an event in which the world may see itself.}{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par Vince said:\~ "Hey, Chief, you're awfully quiet.\~ You're not mad or anything?"
\par "I am not angry."
\par "Yeah . . . well, good.\~ You want a little grass?\~ I got half a lid left."
\par "No."
\par "It's high-grade stuff, man.\~ I got it in Bellingham last week."
\par "I do not smoke your marijuana."
\par "Oh.\~ What }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 are }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 you doing out here?"
\par "I live here.\~ This is my home."
\par "Come on!\~ In that getup?"
\par "This is what I wear when I search for a deformity of the spirit."
\par "A what?"
\par "A thing by which men may know sanity."
\par "You're putting me on."
\par Katsuk thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 I must end it.\~ He cannot be allowed to go and report that he has seen me.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par Vince rubbed his shoulder beneath a pack strap.\~ "This pack sure is heavy."
\par Katsuk said:\~ "You have not yet discovered that having too much is not better than having enough."
\par Nervous laughter jerked in Vince's throat.\~ He said:\~ "Well, I gotta catch up with the others.\~ See you, Chief."\~ He hunched his shoulders into the straps, taking the weight of it off the embankment, stepped past Katsuk.\~ 
There was obvious fear in his movements.
\par Katsuk thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 I cannot pity.\~ That would make the earth fall away from beneath my feet.\~ My knife must go cleanly into this walking youth.\~ }{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 He pulled the knife from its sheath, moved after Vince.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
The knife must pay homage to his blood and break open the time of death.\~ Birth must end with death, with eyes gone dull, memory gone, heart gone, blood gone, all the flesh gone}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588  -- }{
\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 the miracle ended.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par As he thought, he moved:\~ left hand into Vince's hair, yanking the head back, right hand whipping the knife around and across the exposed throat.
\par There was no outcry, just the body slumping back, guided by the hand in the long hair.\~ Katsuk dropped to one knee, caught the weight of the pack on it, held the jerking figure upright.\~ A jet of red gushed from the slashed throat, the l
ucid color of a young life spurting in a bright fountain onto the trail -- a rose petal spurting, ebbing, softly now and now frothing, resurgent, the body twitching, then still.
\par It was done.
\par Katsuk felt that this moment had been following him all his life, now to catch up with him.
\par An ending and a beginning.
\par He continued to support the body, wondered how old this young man had been.\~ Twenty?\~ Perhaps.\~ Whatever his age, it was ended here -- the pleasure and the time passing, all a dream now.\~ Katsuk felt his mind whirling with what he had done.\~ 
Strange visions captured his awareness:\~ all a dream, black and hidden, an evil profile, clouds under water, limbs of air moving with jade ripples, a green crystal, fluid carving traces in his memory.
\par This earth had green blood.
\par He felt the weight of the sagging body.\~ This flesh had been a minor pattern in an overlarge universe.\~ Now it faded.\~ He allowed the body to fall on its left side, stood, and peered uphill toward the log where Hoquat lay hidden.\~ It was a hil
lside suddenly full of green light as clouds exposed the sun.
\par Deep within himself, Katsuk prayed:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Raven, Raven, keep the edge on my hate.\~ O Raven, keep me terrible in revenge.\~
 This is Katsuk, who lay three nights in thy forest, who heeded no thorn, but did thy bidding.\~ This is Katsuk, thy torch, who will set this world afire.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
