\s15\ql \li0\ri0\sb100\sa100\sbauto1\saauto1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\ipgp1 \fs24\lang1049\langfe1049\cgrid\langnp1049\langfenp1049 {\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 \page 
"Why do you pick up those rocks?" Katsuk asked.
\par David held up four pebbles in his left hand.\~ "To count the days.\~ We've been gone four days."
\par "We count by nights," Katsuk said.
\par And Katsuk wondered at himself, trying to teach this essential thing to a hoquat.\~ Four pebbles for the days or four pebbles for nights, what difference could it make for a hoquat?\~ Night and day were 
only separations between degrees of fear for this young man's people.
\par They sat in another bark shelter Katsuk had built, finishing off the last morsels of a grouse Katsuk had snared.\~ The only light was from the fire in the center of the shelter.\~ It cast 
ruddy shadows on the crude structure over them, glistened on the knots tied in rope made from twisted willow which supported the framework.
\par It was full dark outside and there was a pond which had reflected molten copper in the sunset.\~ Now it was a haunted pond full of captured stars.
\par Katsuk had taken the grouse from a giant hemlock near the pond.\~ He had called it a roosting tree.\~ The ground beneath it was white with grouse droppings.\~ The grouse had come sleepily to the hemlock branches at dusk and Katsu
k had snared one with a long pole and a string noose.
\par David belched, sighed, put the last of the grouse bones into the fire pit as Katsuk had instructed him.\~ Pit and bones would be covered up and disguised in the morning.
\par Katsuk had spread cedar boughs under the sleeping bag.\~ He stretched out under the bag with his feet toward the dying fire, said:\~ "Come.\~ We sleep now."
\par David crawled around the fire, slid under the bag.\~ It felt clammy from not being hung to dry in the sun.\~ There was an acid smell to it which mingled with the smoke and burned grease, perspiration, and cedar.
\par The fire burned itself down to a few coals.\~ David felt the night close in around him.\~ Sounds took on fearful shapes.\~ He felt the cedar needles scratching.\~ This was a place so ut
terly foreign to the sounds, sights, and smells of his usual life that he tried to recall things from other times which would fit here.\~ 
All he could bring to mind were the tire-humming whine of a car crossing a steel bridge, the city's smoke, his mother's perfume . . . nothing fitted.\~ One place rejected the other.
\par Softly, he slipped across the border of awareness and into sleep, there to dream.\~ A giant face leaned over him.\~ It was a face much like Katsuk's -- broad, prominent cheekbones, a mane of thick black hair, wide mouth.
\par The mouth opened, said:\~ "You are not yet ready.\~ When you are ready, I will come for you.\~ Pray then, and a wish will be granted you."\~ The mouth closed, but the voice continued:\~ "I will come for you . . . come for you . . . for you . . . you!"\~ 
It reverberated in his skull and filled him with terror.\~ He awoke trembling, sweating, and with a feeling that the voice continued somewhere.
\par "Katsuk?"
\par "Go to sleep."
\par "But I had a dream."
\par "What kind of dream?"\~ There was alertness in the man's voice.
\par "I don't know.\~ It scared me."
\par "What did you dream?"
\par David described it.
\par His voice oddly withdrawn, Katsuk said:\~ "You have a spirit dream."
\par "Was it your god?"
\par "Perhaps."
\par "What does it mean, Katsuk?"
\par "You are the only one who can tell."
\par Katsuk struggled with an empty feeling in his breast.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 A spirit dream for Hoquat!\~ }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
Was it Soul Catcher playing an evil game?\~ There were stories about such things.\~ What a disturbing dream!\~ Hoquat had been granted the right to a wish -- any wish.\~ If he wished to leave the wilderness, Hoquat could do it.
\par "Katsuk, what's a spirit dream?"
\par "That's where you get a spirit guide for your other soul -- in the dream."
\par "You said it could be a god."
\par "It can be a god or a spirit.\~ He tells you what you must do, where you must go."
\par "My dream didn't tell me to go anywhere."
\par "Your dream told you that you aren't yet ready."
\par "Ready for what?"
\par "To go anywhere."
\par "Oh."\~ Silence, then:\~ "That dream scared me."
\par "Ahhh, you see -- the hoquat science doesn't liberate you from the terror of the gods."
\par "Do you really believe that stuff, Katsuk?"
\par His voice low and tense, Katsuk said:\~ "Listen to me!\~ Every person has two souls.\~ One remains in the body.\~ The other travels high or low.\~ It is guided by the kind of life you lead.\~ The soul that travels must have a guide:\~ a spirit or a god."

\par "That isn't what they teach in church."
\par Katsuk snorted.\~ "You doubt, eh?\~ Once, I doubted.\~ It almost destroyed me.\~ I no longer doubt."
\par "Did you get a guide?"
\par "Yes."
\par "Is Raven your guide?"
\par Katsuk felt Soul Catcher stirring within him, said:\~ "You do not understand about guides, Hoquat."
\par David scowled into he darkness.\~ "Can only Indians get --"
\par "Don't call me Indian!"
\par "But you're --"
\par "Indian is a fool's name.\~ You gave it to us.\~ You refused to admit you hadn't found India.\~ Why must I live with your mistake?"
\par David recalled Mrs. Parma, said:\~ "I know a real Indian from India.\~ She works for us.\~ My parents brought her from India."
\par "Everywhere you hoquat go, the natives work for you."
\par "She'd be starving if she still lived in India.\~ I've heard my mother talk about it.\~ People starve there."
\par "People starve everywhere."
\par "Do real Indians get guides?"
\par "Anyone can get a guide."
\par "Do you do it just by dreaming?"
\par "You go into the forest and you pray."
\par "We're in the forest.\~ Could I pray now?"
\par "Sure.\~ Ask Alkuntam to send you a guide."
\par "Is Alkuntam your name for God?"
\par "You could say that."
\par "Did Alkuntam give you your guide?"
\par "You don't understand it, Hoquat.\~ Go to sleep."
\par "But how does your spirit guide you?"
\par "I explained that.\~ It speaks to you."
\par David recalled the dream.\~ "Right in your head?"
\par "Yes."
\par "Did your spirit tell you to kidnap me?"
\par Katsuk felt the boy's questions as a pressure, stirring up wild powers within him.\~ Soul Catcher moved there, stretching.
\par David pressed the question:\~ "Did your spirit tell you?"
\par Katsuk said:\~ "Be silent or I will tie and gag you."\~ He turned away, stretched his feet toward the warmth remaining in the rocks around the fire pit.
\par "}{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 I am Tamanawis speaking to you}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 . . . ."
\par Katsuk heard the spirit so loud he wondered that the boy could not hear it.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 "You have been given the perfect innocent."}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par David said:\~ "When does your spirit speak to you?"
\par "When there is something you need to know," Katsuk whispered.
\par "What do I need to know?"
\par "How to accept my sharp and biting point," Katsuk whispered.
\par "What?"
\par "You need to know how to live that you may die correctly.\~ First, you need to live.\~ Most of you hoquat do not live."
\par "Does your spirit make you talk crazy like that?"
\par Katsuk felt hysterical laughter in his throat, said:\~ "Go to sleep or I will kill you before you have lived."
\par David heard intensity in the words, began to tremble.\~ The man was crazy.\~ He could do anything.\~ He had murdered.
\par Katsuk felt the trembling, reached back, and patted the boy's shoulder.\~ "Do not worry, Hoquat.\~ You will yet live.\~ I promise it."
\par Still the boy's trembling continued.
\par Katsuk sat up, took the old flute from his belt pouch, blew softly into it.\~ He felt the song go out, smoke-yearning sounds in the shelter.
\par For a few moments, Katsuk imagined himself in some old, safe-place with a friend, with a brother.\~ They would share music.\~ They would plan the hunt for the morrow.\~ They would preserve the dignity of this place and of each other.
\par David listened to the low music, lulled by it.
\par Presently, Katsuk stopped, restored the flute to its pouch.\~ Hoquat breathed with the even rhythm of sleep.\~ As though it were a thing of reality which could be seen and touched, Katsuk felt a bond being created between himself and this boy.\~ 
Was it possible they were really brothers in that other world which moved invisibly and soundlessly beside the world of the senses?
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 My brother, Hoquat, }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Katsuk thought.
