David jerked upright into empty blackness.\~ He shivered with fear and cold.\~ He hugged himself to still the trembling, searched for something to place him in a world, any abrasive edge to convey reality.\~ Where was he?
\par He knew why he had awakened.\~ A dream had taken him, loping along the edge of wakening.\~ It had confronted him with a black stone, then green water and rippling glass.\~ The smell of rancid oil had tickled his awareness.\~ Something had chased him.\~ 
Something still ran close behind him, singing softly of things he knew but did not want to hear.\~ Even the awareness that the song contained a meaning terrified him.
\par David exhaled a sobbing breath.\~ Fear shimmered over him with a bass hum of sweat and running and the remembered dream.\~ He felt the white gold pulsebeat of gods and firelight.\~ The thing with meaning pressed close.\~ It was right behind him.\~ 
He felt his muscles wanting to run.\~ His mouth tasted of rusty iron.\~ He felt his throat jerking with sounds he could not make.\~ The thing behind him was going to catch him!\~
 The words of its song draped over his mind, a white-gray whispering, smooth as glass, promising happiness while it presented him with terror.
\par The dream singing persisted.
\par David heard it and tasted bitter acid in his throat.\~ The dream terror washed around him in that faint tide of sound.\~ He shuddered, wondering if he still dreamed, if the sensation of awakening was illusion.
\par A spark of orange light formed in the darkness.\~ He heard movement near the light.\~ Cautiously, he reached up with his left hand.\~ His fingers encountered a rough wood surface.
\par Memory filled him -- a dungeon cave with moldering plank walls.\~ Katsuk had brought them here at dusk, searching out the way, exploring ahead while the boy crouched in shadows.\~ 
This was a secret place used by his people when they broke the hoquat law and hunted game in these mountains.
\par The orange light was a remnant of the tiny fire Katsuk had built in the cave mouth.\~ Movement of shadowy arms flickered across the light -- Katsuk!
\par But the singing continued.\~ Was it Katsuk?\~ No . . . it seemed far away and full of words he could not understand -- a whistling flute and a slow, walking rhythm on a drum.\~ 
Katsuk had played his flute one night and this sounded like a distant parody of that playing.
\par David's fear ebbed.\~ That was real singing, a real drum, and a flute like Katsuk's.\~ There were several voices.
\par }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 The poachers!}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par Katsuk had crept away in the first dark, returning much later to say he recognized the people camped in the trees at the edge of the meadow.
\par A groan came from near the fire.\~ Was that Katsuk?\~ David strained to hear what Katsuk was doing.\~ He wondered:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Should I let him know I'm awake?\~ Why did he groan?}{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par Again, the groan sounded.
\par David cleared his throat.
\par "You are awake!"\~ Katsuk hurled the words at him from the cave's mouth.
\par David recoiled at the madness in Katsuk's voice, was unable to answer.
\par "I know you are awake," Katsuk said, calmer now and nearer.\~ "It will be daylight soon.\~ We go then."
\par David sensed the presence over him, blackness in blackness.\~ He tried to swallow in a dry throat, managed:\~ "Where will we go?"
\par "To my people."
\par "Is that them . . . singing?"
\par "There is no singing."
\par David listened.\~ The forest outside the cave gave off only the soughing of wind in trees, faint drippings, stirrings, and rustlings.\~ Katsuk pressed something hot beneath the boughs beside David:\~ another heated rock.
\par "I heard singing," David said.
\par "You dreamed it."
\par "I heard it!"
\par "It is gone now."
\par "What was it?"
\par "Those of my people who have eaten spirits."
\par "What?"
\par "Try to sleep a little longer."
\par David remembered the dream.\~ "No."\~ He pressed against the moldering boards beside him.\~ "Where are your people?"
\par "Everywhere around us."
\par "In the forest?"
\par "Everywhere!\~ If you sleep, the spirit eaters may come to you and explain their song."
\par With sudden realization, David asked:\~ "You're trying to tell me it was ghosts singing!"
\par "Spirits."
\par "I don't want to sleep."
\par "Have you prayed for your spirit?"
\par "No!\~ What was that song?"
\par "It was a song asking for power over that which no human can defeat."
\par David groped in the darkness for the sleeping bag, pulled it around him.\~ He leaned over the place where Katsuk had placed the heated rock.\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Crazy Katsuk!\~ He makes no sense.}{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par "You will not sleep?" Katsuk asked.
\par "How soon will it be daylight?" David countered.
\par "Within the hour."
\par Katsuk's hand came out of the dark, pressed David toward the warm rock.\~ In a soothing tone, Katsuk said:\~ "Go to sleep.\~ You dreamed an important dream and ran from it."
\par David stiffened.\~ "How do you know?"
\par "Sleep," Katsuk said.
\par David stretched out over the rock.\~ His body drank the warmth.\~ The musky, falling, swimming attraction of sleep radiated from the warmth.\~ He did not even feel it when Katsuk's hand released him.
\par He lapsed into a state with no sharp edges.\~ Magic and ghosts and dreams:\~ They were gauze in an orange wind.\~ Nothing completed a sensation of touch.\~ Everything blended, one blur into another:\~ warmth in
to the cedar boughs beneath him, Katsuk returning to the cave's mouth, the dream into the chill where the rock's warmth failed to reach him.\~ Vagueness everywhere.
\par All blurred and faded.
\par He felt his childhood fading, thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 I am becoming a man.\~ }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
Memory treasures stored up against just such an awakening, receded into gray impressions -- pictures he recalled pasting in a book, the rungs of a staircase where he had peered through to watch guests arriving, being tucked into bed by a benign figure who
se face was lost in a halo of silver hair.
\par David sensed warm orange firelight.\~ Katsuk had built up the fire at the cave's mouth.\~ He felt damp cold under his back.\~ A night bird screamed twice.\~ Katsuk groaned.
\par The groan sent a shock all through David.
\par Vagueness vanished, taking sleep and the dreams of his childhood.\~ He thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Katsuk is sick.\~ It's a sickness no one can heal.\~ Katsuk has caught a spirit and eaten it.\~
 He has the power no human can defeat.\~ That's what he meant about the song!\~ The birds obey him.\~ They hide us.\~ He has gone into someplace where humans can't follow.\~ He has gone where the song is . . . where I'm afraid to go.}{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par David sat up, wondered at such thoughts coming all unbidden into his mind.\~ Those were not the thoughts of childhood.\~ He had thought real things, penetrating things.\~ They were thoughts from immediate pressures of life and death.
\par As though his thoughts had called it into being, the song started up once more.\~ It began out of nothing, the words still unintelligible, even it's direction undefined . . . somewhere outside.
\par "Katsuk?" David said.
\par "You hear the singing?"\~ He spoke from near the fire.
\par "What is it?"
\par "Some of my people.\~ They hold a sing."
\par "Why?"
\par "They try to call me out of the mountains."
\par "Do they want you to turn me loose?"
\par "They have eaten a small spirit, Hoquat.\~ It is not as powerful as my spirit."
\par "What're you going to do?"
\par "When it is daylight, we will go to them.\~ I will take you to them and show them the power of my spirit."
