\s15\ql \li0\ri0\sb100\sa100\sbauto1\saauto1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\ipgp1 \fs24\lang1049\langfe1049\cgrid\langnp1049\langfenp1049 {\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 \page 
In the last of the darkness, Katsuk stood outside the cave which was an ancient mine shaft high on the hillside above the lake.\~ He saw lights flickering in the branches below him, campfires beneath the fog that veiled the valley.\~ 
The lights glowed and swam as though they were moving phosphor in water, shapes blurred in fog ripples.
\par He thought:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 My people.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par He had crept close and identified them in the night, not by their hoquat names but by their tribal names which were shared only with those who could be trusted.\~ 
They were Duck Woman, Eyes on Tree, Hates Fish, Elk Jumping, One-ball Grandfather, Moon Water. . . .\~ In his own tongue now, he said their names:
\par "Tchukawl, Kipskiltch, Ishkawch, Klanitska, Naykletak, Tskanay. . . .\~ "
\par Tskanay was there, thinking of herself as Mary Kletnik, no doubt.\~ He tried to summon a Charles Hobuhet memory of Mary Kletnik.\~ Nothing came into his mind.\~ She was there, but behind a veil.\~ Why was she hiding?\~
 He sensed a lithe shape naked in firelight, a voice murmuring, fingers touching flesh, a softness which demanded dangerous things of him.
\par She was a threat.
\par He understood this now.\~ Tskanay had been important to Charles Hobuhet.\~ She might strike through to the center which was Katsuk.\~ Women had powers.\~ Soul Catcher must deal with her.
\par The sun came over the edge of the valley.\~ Katsuk looked beyond the bowl of fog to the mountain suspended in the dawn.\~ Black splotches of rock stood out against snow as white as a goat-hair blanket.\~ 
The mountain was an ancient shape pressed hard against the sky and left hanging there.
\par Katsuk prayed then:\~ }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Soul Catcher protect me from that woman.\~ Guard my strength.\~ Keep my hatred pure.}{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
\par He went into the mine-cave then, awakened the boy, and fed him chocolate and peanuts from the pack.\~ Hoquat ate hungrily, unaware that Katsuk was not eating.\~ The boy said nothing of his dream, but Katsuk recalled it, 
sensing the dangerous forces being gathered against him.
\par Hoquat had dreamed of a spirit who would grant any wish.\~ The spirit had said he was not yet ready.\~ Ready for what?\~ For the sacrifice?\~ It said something that Hoquat had a spirit in his dream.\~ That didn't happen to everyone.\~
 That was a sign of real powers.\~ How else could this be, though?\~ The sacrifice must be a great thing to have any meaning.\~ The }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Innocent }{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 must go into the spirit world with a great voice which could not be denied.\~ Both worlds must hear him or the death would be meaningless.
\par Katsuk shook his head.\~ It was disturbing, but this was no morning for dreams.\~ This would be a day for testing the realities of the fleshly world.
\par He went back outside then and saw that the sun had burned part of the fog from the valley.\~ The lake was a mirror catching the bright flare of sunlight.\~ It filled the valley with pale clarity.\~
 A black bear came out into the meadow above the lake, drank the air with its tongue hanging like a dog's.\~ It caught the scent of humans, whirled, and loped back into the trees.
\par Katsuk stripped off the hoquat clothing, stood in only the loincloth and the moccasins Janiktaht had made, the medicine pouch hanging at his waist.
\par The boy came out.\~ Katsuk handed the hoquat clothing to him, said:\~ "Put this in the pack.\~ Stuff the sleeping bag on top, and hide the pack beyond where we slept."
\par "Why?"
\par "Do it and come back here."
\par David shrugged, obeyed.\~ Presently, he returned, said:\~ "I'll bet you're cold."
\par "I am not cold.\~ Come.\~ We go to my people now."\~ He led the way at a fast walk which had the boy trotting to keep up.
\par They went down across a bracken slope, acid green with red-leaved vines creeping through the green.\~ A gray prow of rock jutted from the slope.\~ They went around the rock and plunged into a dark trail through trees.
\par David was panting by the time they splashed across rocky shallows in the creek.\~ Katsuk seemed unaware of exertion, keeping up that steady, long stride.\~ There were cottonwoods by the creek -- pale, yellow-green moss on their trunks.\~ 
The trail went through wet salal, emerged on a narrow ledge thick with spruce and cedar, a few tall hemlocks.\~ Four crude huts, one of them as large as all the other three together, were spaced among the trees about fifty feet apart.\~ 
All had been built of split cedar boards dug into the needle duff of the ground and lashed to a pole framework.\~ David could see the lashings of twisted willow rope.\~ The largest hut had a low door curtained by raw elk-hide.
\par As Katsuk and the boy came in sight of the door, the curtain lifted and a young woman emerged.\~ Katsuk stopped, held his captive with a hand on the boy's shoulder.
\par The young woman came fully outside before she saw them.\~ She stopped then, put a hand to her cheek.\~ Recognition was obvious in her stare.
\par David stood locked under Katsuk's grip.\~ He wondered what was in Katsuk's mind.\~ Katsuk and the young woman just looked at each other without speaking.\~ David studied the woman, his senses abnormally alert.\~ Her hair was parted i
n the middle, hanging loosely over her shoulders.\~ The ends were braided, tied with white string.\~ Pockmarks disfigured her left cheek, showing around the hand she held there.\~ Her cheeks were broad.\~
 They glistened, and her eyes were set deeply into the flesh.\~ Her figure was full and slender beneath a red-purple dress which stopped just below her knees.
\par All the way down the mountain, David had told himself Katsuk's people would end this nightmare.\~ The old days of Indians and white captives were gone forever.\~ These people had come here as part of the search for Katsuk.\~ 
Now David saw fear in the young woman's eyes and began to doubt his hopes.
\par She dropped her hand, said:\~ "Charlie."
\par Katsuk gave no response.
\par She looked at David, back to Katsuk.\~ "I didn't think it would work."
\par Katsuk stirred, said:\~ "Didn't think }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 what }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 would work?"\~ His voice sounded strained.
\par "The sing."
\par "You think I came because they sang me in?"
\par "Why not?"
\par Katsuk released David's shoulder, said:\~ "Hoquat, this is Tskanay . . . an old friend."
\par Coming toward them, she said:\~ "My name is Mary Kletnik."
\par "Your name is Tskanay," Katsuk said.\~ "Moon Water."
\par "Oh, stop that nonsense, Charlie," she said.\~ "You --"
\par "Do not call me Charlie."
\par Although he spoke softly, his tone stopped her.\~ Again, she put a hand to her pockmarked cheek.\~ "But. . . ."
\par "I have another name now:\~ Katsuk."
\par "Katsuk?"
\par "You know what it means."
\par She shrugged "The center . . . kind of."
\par "Kind of," he sneered.\~ He touched the boy.\~ "This is Hoquat, the Innocent who will answer for all of our innocents."
\par "You don't really. . . ."
\par "The reality I show you, it will be the only reality."
\par Her glance went to the knife at his waist.
\par "Nothing that simple," Katsuk said.\~ "Where are the others?"
\par "Most of them went out before dawn . . . searching."
\par "For me?"
\par She nodded.
\par David's heart leaped at her response.\~ Katsuk's people }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 were }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 here to help.\~ They were searching.\~ He said:\~
 "My name is David Marshall.\~ I --"
\par A stinging backhand blow sent him reeling.
\par Tskanay put both hands to her mouth, stifled a scream.
\par In a conversational tone, Katsuk said:\~ "Your name is Hoquat.\~ Do not forget again."\~ He turned to the young woman.\~ "We spent the night in the old mine.\~ We even built a fire.\~ Why did your searchers not search there?"
\par She lowered her hands, did not answer.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "Do you still think your pitiful sing brought me in?"
\par Her throat convulsed with swallowing.
\par David, his cheek burning from the blow, glared angrily at Katsuk, but fear kept him rooted.
\par "Who is still in camp?" Katsuk asked.
\par Tskanay said:\~ "Your Aunt Cally and old Ish, that I know of.\~ Probably one or two of the younger boys.\~ They don't like to go out in the cold too early."
\par "The story of our lives," Katsuk said.\~ "Do you have a radio?"
\par "No."
\par The elkhide curtain behind her lifted.\~ An old man emerged -- long nose, gray hair to his shoulders, a crane figure.\~ He wore bib overalls and a green wool shirt that flopped loosely on his thin frame.\~ Caulked boots covered his feet.\~
 He carried a lever-action rifle in his right hand.
\par David, seeing the rifle, allowed his hopes to grow once more.\~ He studied the old man:\~ pale face full of wrinkles, eyes sunken above high cheeks.\~ A dark, elemental spirit lay in the eyes.\~ His hair was twisted together like old kelp that had dried a
nd rotted on a beach.
\par "Been listening," the old man said.\~ His voice was high and clear.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "Hello, Ish."
\par Ish came fully out of the door, let the curtain drop.\~ He moved with a limp, favoring his left foot.\~ "Katsuk, eh?"
\par "That is my name."\~ Katsuk spoke with a subtle air of deference.
\par "Why?" Ish asked.\~ He advanced to a position beside Tskanay.\~ A distance of about ten feet separated them from Katsuk and the boy.
\par David sensed the contest between these two, looked at Katsuk.
\par "We both know what opens the mind," Katsuk said.
\par "Solitude and suffering," Ish said.\~ "So you think you're a shaman."
\par "You use the correct word, Ish.\~ I'm surprised."
\par "I've had a }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 little }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 education, boy."
\par Katsuk said:\~ "I sought the old ways.\~ I suffered with hunger and cold in the high mountains.\~ I gained a spirit."
\par "You're a woods Indian now, eh?"
\par In a cold, hard voice, Katsuk said:\~ "Do not call me Indian."
\par "Okay," Ish said.\~ He shifted his grip on the rifle.
\par David looked from the rifle to Katsuk, hardly dared to breathe, afraid he might call attention to himself.
\par Ish said:\~ "You really think you got a spirit?"
\par Tskanay said:\~ "Oh, this is idiot talk!"
\par Katsuk said:\~ "I will not be disinherited by my own people in my own land.\~ I know why you are here.\~ My spirit tells me."
\par "Why are we here?" Ish asked.
\par "You used the excuse of hunting for me to }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 poach }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 in your own land.\~ 
You came to break the hoquat laws, to kill game your families need to survive and which is ours by right!"
\par The old man grinned.\~ "Didn't need a spirit to tell you that.\~ You think we weren't really hunting for you?"
\par "I heard the sing," Katsuk said.
\par "It brought you in, too!" Tskanay said.
\par "Sure did," Ish agreed.
\par Katsuk shook his head.\~ "No, uncle of my father, your sing did not bring me in.\~ I came to show you my rank."
\par "You didn't even know I was here," Ish protested.\~ "I heard you ask Mary."
\par "Tskanay," Katsuk corrected him.
\par "Mary, Tskanay -- what's the difference?"
\par "You }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 know }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 the difference, Ish."
\par David realized suddenly that, despite his glib tone, the old man was terrified and trying to hide it.\~ Why was he afraid?\~ He had a rifle and Katsuk only had the knife.\~ 
The fear was there, though -- in the pallor, in the stiffness of his grin, the tension in his old muscles.\~ And Katsuk knew it!
\par "So I know the difference," Ish muttered.
\par "I will show you," Katsuk said.\~ He spread his arms, lifted his face to the sky.\~ "Raven," he said, his voice low, "show them that my spirit is all powerful."
\par The old man sighed, said:\~ "That sure as hell isn't why we sent you to the university."
\par "Raven," Katsuk said, louder this time.
\par "Stop calling your damned bird," Tskanay said.\~ "Raven's been dead for a hundred years at least."
\par "Raven!" Katsuk screamed.
\par A wooden door banged in one of the huts off to the left.\~ Two boys about David's age emerged, stood staring at the scene in the clearing.
\par Katsuk lowered his head, folded his arms.
\par David said:\~ "I saw him bring the birds once."\~ Immediately, he felt foolish.\~ The others ignored him.\~ Did they doubt him?\~ "I }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 did," }{
\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 he insisted.
\par Tskanay was looking at him now.\~ She shook her head sharply.\~ David saw that she, too, was fighting down terror.\~ She was angry, also.\~ Her eyes flashed with it.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "I accept what Raven gives."\~ He began singing, a low chant with harsh, clicking sounds.
\par Ish said:\~ "Stop that!"
\par Tskanay looked puzzled.\~ "That's just names."
\par "Names of his dead," the old man said.\~ His eyes glittered as he glanced around the clearing.
\par Katsuk broke off his chant, said:\~ "You felt them last night during your sing!"
\par "Don't talk nonsense," the old man growled, but there was fear in his voice.\~ It trembled and broke.
\par "Felt }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 what?" }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 Tskanay demanded.
\par Cold gripped David's chest.\~ He }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 knew }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 what Katsuk meant:\~ There were spirits in this place.\~ 
David sensed a dirge humming in the trees.\~ He shivered.
\par "While you sang, I heard them here," Katsuk said.\~ He touched his chest.\~ "They said:\~ 'We are the canoe people, the whale people.\~ Where is our ocean?\~ What are you doing here?\~ This lake is not our ocean.\~ You have run away.\~
 The whales taunt us.\~ They spout only a spear's throw from the beach.\~ Once, they would not have dared this.'\~ That is what the spirits told me."
\par Ish cleared his throat.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "Raven protects me."
\par The old man shook his head, started to lift the rifle.\~ As he moved, a single raven flew in through the trees from the lake.\~ Its pinions clattered in the clearing.\~
 It alighted on the ridge of the largest hut, tipped its head to stare at the people below it.
\par Ish and Tskanay had turned their heads to follow the flight.\~ Tskanay turned back immediately.\~ Ish took longer to study the bird before returning his attention to Katsuk.
\par David kept his attention on Katsuk.\~ What a thing that was -- to summon the raven.
\par Katsuk stared into the old man's eyes, said:\~ "You will call me Katsuk."
\par Ish took a deep, shuddering breath, lowered the rifle.
\par Tskanay put both hands to her cheeks, lowered them guiltily when she saw David glance at her.\~ Her eyes said:\~ "I don't believe this and neither do you."
\par David felt sorry for her.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "You, of all our people, Ish, must know what I am.\~ You have seen the spirits work in men before this.\~ I know it.\~ My grandfather told me.\~ You might have been a }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 
shichta, }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 you, a great leader of our people."
\par Ish coughed, then:\~ "Lot of damned nonsense.\~ That bird's just a coincidence.\~ I haven't believed in that stuff for years."
\par Softly, Katsuk asked:\~ "How many years?"
\par Tskanay said:\~ "Do any of you }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 really }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 believe he called that bird in here?"
\par David whispered:\~ "He did."
\par "How many years?" Katsuk insisted.
\par "Since I saw the light of reason," Ish said.
\par "Hoquat reason," Katsuk said.\~ "Ever since you fell for the hoquat religion."
\par "By God, boy. . . ."
\par "That's it, isn't it?"\~ Katsuk demanded.\~ "You swallowed the hoquat religion like a halibut eating the bait.\~ They pulled you right in.\~ You swallowed it, even though you knew it took you out of all touch with our past."
\par "That's blasphemy, boy!"
\par "I am not }{\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 boy!\~ }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 I am Katsuk.\~ I am the center.\~ I say }{
\i\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 you }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 blaspheme!\~ You deny the powers that are ours by right of inheritance."
\par "That's damned nonsense!"
\par "Then why don't you shoot me?"\~ He screamed it, leaning toward the old man.
\par David held his breath.
\par Tskanay backed away.
\par Ish hefted the rifle.\~ As he moved, the raven on the roof squawked once.\~ Ish almost dropped the rifle in lowering it.\~ His eyes reflected terror now, peering at Katsuk as though he were trying to see inside the younger man.
\par "Now, you know," Katsuk said.\~ He waved his right arm.
\par At the gesture, the raven leaped into the air, flew back toward the lake.
\par "What is my name?" Katsuk demanded.
\par "Katsuk," the old man whispered.\~ His shoulders sagged.\~ The rifle dragged at his arm as though he wanted to drop it.
\par Katsuk gestured at David.\~ "This is Hoquat."
\par "Hoquat," the old man agreed.
\par Katsuk strode between Ish and Tskanay, went to the elkhide curtain.\~ He lifted the curtain, turned back to the girl.\~ "Tskanay, you will keep watch on Hoquat.\~ See that he doesn't try to run away.\~ It is too soon for him to die."\~ 
He went into the hut, dropping the curtain.
\par "He's crazy," David whispered.\~ "He's wild crazy."
\par Tskanay turned on the old man.\~ "Why did you cave in like that?\~ The boy's right.\~ Charlie's --"
\par "Shut up!" Ish snapped.\~ "He's lost to you, Mary.\~ Understand me?\~ You'll never have him.\~ I know.\~ I've seen it before.\~ He's lost to all of us.\~ I've seen it."
\par "You've seen it," she sneered.\~ "Why, you old fool, you just stood there with that rifle while he --"
\par "You saw the bird!"
\par "The bird!"
\par "It could just as well have been lightning to strike us dead!"
\par "You're as crazy as he is!"
\par "Are you blind, girl?\~ I was just talking to keep up my nerve.\~ I didn't even have to see him call that bird.\~ You can feel the power in him.\~ He didn't come in because of our sing.\~ He came to show us his power."
\par She shook her head.\~ "Then What're you going to do?"
\par "Going to wait for the others and tell them."
\par }{\insrsid8201588 "What're you going to tell them?"
\par "That they better watch out before they go up against Katsuk.\~ Where's Cally?"
\par "She went out before I did . . . about ten minutes."
\par "When she gets back, tell her to fix the house for a big meeting.\~ And don't let that kid there get away from you.\~ You do, Katsuk'll kill you."
\par "And you'd just stand there and let him!"
\par "Damned right I would.\~ Don't catch me going up against a real spirit.\~ Soul Catcher's got that one."
