It began to rain intermittently soon after they left the clearing of the huts:\~ rain, then moonlight, rain, moon.\~ It was raining steadily and hard before they reached the old mine shaft.\~ There was distant lightning and thunder.\~ Da
vid, allowing himself to be dragged along in the darkness, wondered if Katsuk was creating the trail one step at a time out of his magic.\~ Katsuk could not possibly see his way in the wet blackness.
\par All the way up the hill, Katsuk chanted and raged.
\par David, his heart palpitating, heard the word-ravenings and understood only the rage.\~ Wet branches clawed at him.\~ He tripped on roots, slipped in mud.\~ He was drenched by the time they reached the shaft.
\par Katsuk's mind was in turmoil.\~ He thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 It was the truth.\~ They know I told them truth.\~ Still they fear.\~ They do not give me all their thoughts.\~ My own people are lost to me.\~
 They do not want the powers I could give them.\~ My own people!}{\insrsid8201588 
\par He pulled Hoquat into the shelter of the mine shaft, released him.\~ Water ran from them.\~ Katsuk pressed his hands against the chilkat loincloth.\~ Rivulets ran down his legs.\~ He thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 We must rest, then go on.\~
 Some of my people are fools.\~ They could tell the hoquat where I am.\~ There must be a reward.\~ Some have the hoquat sickness.\~ They could do it for money.\~ My own people deny me a home in their thoughts.\~ There is no home.\~
 My own people turn away.\~ No one will come to meet me.\~ I am truly homeless.}{\insrsid8201588 
\par How could he rest here?\~ Katsuk wondered.\~ He could feel his own people down there by the lake -- restless, disturbed, divided, arguing.\~ They had heard his words and felt his meaning, but all in a language which blasphemed what he held sacred.
\par }{\i\insrsid8201588 No darkness will ever rest me.\~ I will be a ghost spirit.\~ Not even Tskanay supports me.}{\insrsid8201588 
\par He thought of how Tskanay had looked at him.\~ Her eyes had seen him and found him alien.\~ She had given her body to the boy, trying to swallow innocence.\~ She had thought to make Hoquat unfit.\~ She had failed.\~ Hoquat's shame reinforced his
 innocence.\~ He was more innocent now.
\par Katsuk stared into the black emptiness of the old mine shaft.\~ He sensed the dimensions of it with his memory, with his skin, his nose, his ears.\~ There were ghost spirits here, too.\~ The boy's teeth chattered.\~ Hoquat's fear could almost be touched.

\par The boy whispered:\~ "Katsuk?"
\par "Yes."
\par "Where are we?"
\par "In the cave."
\par "The old mine?"
\par "Yes."
\par "Are y-you g-going t-to b-build a f-f-fire?"
\par Lightning gave a brief flicker of illumination:\~ the cave mouth, dripping trees, rain slanting down.\~ Thunder followed, close, a crash that made the boy gasp.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "Perhaps we have too much fire."
\par The world suddenly was shattered by a barren plume of lightning so close they smelled the hell fragrance of it as the thunder shook them.
\par The boy whirled, clung to Katsuk's arm.
\par Again, lightning flickered against wet blackness, this time near the lake.\~ The thunderclap came like an echo of the one before it.
\par The boy trembled and shook against Katsuk.
\par "That was Kwahoutze," Katsuk said.\~ "That was the god in water, the spirit of all the regions brought together by water."
\par "It was s-so close."
\par "He tells us this is still his land."
\par Again, the lightning flashed -- beyond the lake now.\~ Thunder followed, rumbling.
\par The boy said:\~ "I don't want to steal your land."
\par Katsuk patted his shoulder.\~ "And I was going to over-proud my enemies.\~ This land does not know who owns it."
\par David said:\~ "I'm sorry we stole your land."
\par "I know, Hoquat.\~ You are truly innocent.\~ You are one of the few who feel why this land is sacred to me.\~ You are the immigrant invader.\~ You have not learned how to worship this land.\~ It is my land because I worship it.\~
 The spirits know, but the land does not know."
\par Silence fell between them.\~ Katsuk freed himself from the boy's grip, thinking:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Hoquat depends upon me for his strength, but that can be dangerous for me.\~ If he takes strength from me, I must take strength from him.\~
 We could become one person, both of us Soul Catcher.\~ Who could I sacrifice then?}{\insrsid8201588 
\par David listened to the sound of falling rain, the distant progression of lightning and thunder.\~ Presently, he said:\~ "Katsuk?"
\par "Yes."
\par "Are you going to kill me . . . like your aunt said?"
\par "I use you to send a message."
\par David chewed his lower lip.\~ "But your aunt said. . . ."
\par "Unless you tell me to do it, I will not kill you."
\par Relief flooded through David.\~ He drew a deep breath.\~ "But I'd never tell you to --"
\par "Hoquat!\~ Why do you prefer mouth-talk to body-talk?"
\par Katsuk moved into the shaft.
\par Rebuked, David stood trembling.\~ The old madness had returned to Katsuk's voice.
\par Katsuk found the pack by smelling the mustiness of it.\~ He squatted, felt the fabric, removed matches, a packet of tinder.\~ Presently, he had a small fire going.\~ Smoke drifted in a gray line along the ceiling.\~
 The flame cast raw shadows on old beams and rock.
\par David approached, stood close to the fire, trembling, holding his hands out to the warmth.
\par Katsuk gathered the cedar boughs of their bed, spread the sleeping bag.\~ He stretched out on the bag with his back against a rotting beam.
\par The boy stood with his head just beneath the smoke.\~ The gray line above him was like a spirit essence drifting toward the dark entrance into the world.
\par Katsuk withdrew the willow flute from his waistband, touched it to his lips.\~ He blew softly.\~ The clear sound circled upward into the smoke, carrying his mind with it.\~ He played the song of cedar, 
the song to placate cedar when they took bark for mats and clothing, for rope and net string.\~ He blew the song softly.\~ It was a bird singing deep in the shade of cedar boughs.
\par Sweetly on the song, he sensed a vision:\~ Janiktaht carrying a basket piled with curling shreds of cedar bark.\~ And he thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 This is better for Janiktaht.\~ I should not be forever seeking her face among the faces of strangers.}
{\insrsid8201588 
\par The words of the song echoed in his mind:\~ "Life maker cedar . . . fire maker cedar --"
\par The vision of Janiktaht moved within him.\~ She grew larger, larger, older, uglier.\~ The basket of cedar bark shriveled.
\par Sweat broke out on his forehead.\~ His mind stumbled.\~ He dropped the flute.
\par David asked:\~ "Why did you stop?"
\par Katsuk sat up, stared at the evil flute beside him.\~ He shook his head.\~ The movement was like wind swaying cedar boughs.\~ The cedar band around his head pressed into his skull.\~ He knew it might crush his head.\~ He could not remove the band.
\par "Keep that sickness away from me," he muttered.
\par "What?"
\par "I don't want to be killed by that sickness."
\par "What's wrong?"
\par Katsuk glared across the fire at the boy.\~ "What has made me so unlucky?"
\par "Are you unlucky?"\~ David didn't understand the conversation but felt his participation being demanded.
\par "I am overcome by it," Katsuk said.\~ "I have been found by Short-Life-Maker."
\par "Katsuk, you're talking awfully funny."
\par "Evil words have been sent against me!"
\par "What words?"
\par "I have enemies.\~ They have cursed me.\~ They wish me to die quickly.\~ My own people!\~ They have no mercy."
\par David moved around the fire, squatted beside the sleeping bag.\~ He touched Katsuk's flute.\~ "I liked the music.\~ Will you play some more?"
\par "No!"
\par "Why?"
\par "Because I have discovered my omen tree."
\par The boy stared at him, puzzled.
\par Katsuk closed his eyes.\~ He pictured a cedar, a great cedar with bulging roots, glossy needles, a cedar deep in the forest, sucking at the earth's belly and piling its boughs high, a skirt of long boughs at the bottom that leaned outward int
o a thick bed of leaf mold.
\par "My omen tree," Katsuk whispered.
\par "What's an omen tree?" David asked.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "I was my mother's firstborn."\~ He opened his eyes, stared upward into the ruddy smoke.\~ "Her brother carved a little canoe for me.\~ He made a tiny fish spear.\~ He made a rattle box.\~ He made all of these things from cedar."
\par "That makes an omen tree?"
\par Katsuk spoke in a distant voice:\~ "My parents were in a cedar canoe when they died.\~ Janiktaht stole a cedar canoe when she. . . .\~ The splinter!\~ I was very sick that time with the splinter in my knee.\~ They said I could lose the leg.\~
 It was a cedar splinter.\~ All this is very clear, Hoquat.\~ Someone in my family has offended cedar.\~ That is the end of me, then."
\par "Do you really believe that stuff?"
\par "Don't tell me what I believe!"\~ He glared at the boy.
\par David recoiled.\~ "But. . . ."
\par "We have burned cedar, carved her.\~ We have made rafts of cedar, kindling wood, long planks, and shakes to keep off the rain.\~ But we did not show how thankful we were to her.\~ Cedar's heart aches.\~
 We have stepped on her roots, bruised them, and never thought about it.\~ I rest on cedar right now!\~ How stupid!"
\par He leaped off the sleeping bag, jerked it aside, began gathering up the boughs.\~ He carried them outside, stacked them in the rain.\~ His skin glistened with water when he returned.\~
 He squatted, gathered the fallen needles, sweeping them together, searching out every one.\~ When he had them all, he took them out into the rain, scattered them.
\par "Cedar!" he shouted.\~ "I give you back what I took!\~ I beg forgiveness!\~ I ask my spirits to give you this message.\~ I did not mean to harm you.\~ Cedar, forgive me!"
\par David squatted by the fire, watched wide-eyed.\~ Katsuk was insane!
\par Katsuk returned to the fire, put a damp spruce limb into the flame.\~ "See," he said, "I do not burn cedar."
\par David stood, pressed his back against the rock wall.
\par Katsuk nodded his head to the flames.\~ Falsetto whines came out of his throat, monotone grunts.
\par David said:\~ "Are you praying?"
\par "I need a language to explain how I feel.\~ I need a language that has never been heard before.\~ Cedar must hear me and know my prayer."
\par David listened for words, heard none.\~ The sounds were hypnotic.\~ He felt his eyelids drooping.\~ Presently, he went to the sleeping bag, wrapped himself in it, stretched out on the hard ground.
\par Katsuk went on with his odd noises, groaning, whining.\~ Even after the fire had reduced itself to a glowing, orange eye, the sound went on and on and on.\~ The boy heard it occasionally as he half awoke from sleep.
