The first thing David saw when he awoke was thin pillars of rain slanting across the mine entrance.\~ The world outside was full of dawn's broken light, misty gray-white.\~ Katsuk was nowhere to be seen, but ravens clamored somewhere outside.
\par David trembled at the sound.
\par He slid out of the sleeping bag, stood up.\~ It was cold.\~ Moisture filled the air.\~ He went to the mouth of the shaft, stared around him, shivering.
\par The rain slackened.
\par David turned, peered into the shaft.\~ Not likely Katsuk had gone back deeper into there.\~ Where was he?
\par The ravens called from the trees down by the lake.\~ Mist hid them.\~ David felt hunger grip his stomach.\~ He coughed.
\par The wind remained strong.\~ It blew from the west, pushing clouds against the peaks beyond the lake valley.\~ Branches whipped in the wind atop the ridge, chopped the light.
\par }{\i\insrsid8201588 Should I go down to the huts?\~ }{\insrsid8201588 David wondered.
\par He could see the game trail they had climbed in the night.\~ The rain stopped, but water dripped from every leaf he could see.
\par David thought of the huts, the people.\~ They had allowed Katsuk to take his captive away.\~ They wouldn't help.\~ Cally had said as much.
\par He heard splashing on the game trail, grunting.
\par Katsuk climbed into view.\~ He wore a loincloth and moccasins.\~ The sheathed knife flopped against his side with every step.\~ His body glistened with wetness, but he seemed unaware of water or cold.\~
 He climbed onto the ledge at the mouth of the mine and David saw that he carried a package.\~ It was wrapped in dirty cloth.
\par Katsuk thrust the package toward the boy, said:\~ "Smoked fish.\~ Cally sent it."
\par David took the package, opened it with cold-stiffened fingers.\~ The fish was bright red, oily, and hard.\~ He broke off a piece, chewed.\~ It tasted salty and sweet.\~ He swallowed and immediately felt better.
\par He took another mouthful of fish, spoke around it:\~ "You went down to see your friends?"
\par "Friends," Katsuk said, his voice flat.\~ He wondered if a shaman ever had friends.\~ Probably not.\~ You went outside human associations when you gained spirit powers.\~ Presently, he glanced at the boy, said:\~ "You didn't try to escape again."
\par "I thought about it."\~ Defiant.
\par "Why didn't you try?"
\par "I heard the ravens."
\par Katsuk nodded.\~ It was logical.\~ He said:\~ "That lightning last night -- it hit the big spruce beside the house where my }{\i\insrsid8201588 friends }{\insrsid8201588 were talking.\~ They were arguing whether 
to turn me over to the hoquat police when pieces of the tree smashed through the roof."\~ He smiled without mirth.
\par David swallowed a bite of fish.\~ "Was anybody hurt?"
\par "A fish rack fell on Tskanay.\~ It bruised her arm.\~ Ish was burned.\~ He tried to jump across the fire.\~ They were not hurt much, but they no longer discuss what to do with me."
\par David chewed silently, studying his captor, trying not to betray awe at this revelation.\~ It was one more thing to confirm the powers Katsuk controlled.\~ He could bring down the lightning.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "They don't want me to send more lightning."
\par David sensed something cynical and doubting in Katsuk's tone, asked:\~ "Did you make the lightning?"
\par "Maybe.\~ I don't know.\~ But that's what they think."
\par "What did you tell them?"
\par "I told them an owl's tongue will bring rain.\~ I told them Raven can create fire.\~ They know this, but they've been taught the hoquat ways of doubting their own past.\~ Have you had enough of that fish?"
\par "Yes."\~ David nodded numbly.\~ To have lightning silence those who could harm you!\~ To know what would bring rain and fire!\~ What powers those were.
\par Katsuk took the package of fish from the boy's hand, wrapped it tightly, thrust it into his pouch.\~ He said:\~ "Will you follow, or will you try to escape?"
\par David swallowed a lump in his throat.\~ Escape?\~ Where could he run that Katsuk's powers would not follow?\~ But there had to be some way out of this nightmare.\~ There must be some way to break free of Katsuk.
\par "Answer me," Katsuk ordered.
\par David thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 He'll know if I try to lie to him.\~ }{\insrsid8201588 He said:\~ "If I find a way to get away from you, I will."
\par }{\i\insrsid8201588 The honesty of innocence, }{\insrsid8201588 Katsuk thought.\~ Admiration for this hoquat youth rose in him.\~ What a magnificent sacrifice Hoquat would make.\~ Truly, this was the Great In
nocent, one to answer for all of those the hoquat had slain.
\par Katsuk asked:\~ "But will you follow me now?"
\par "I'll follow."\~ Sullen.\~ "Where're we going?"
\par "We will climb today.\~ We will go over the mountain into another valley where there are no man trails."
\par "Why?"
\par "I am pulled in that direction."
\par "Shall I get the pack and the sleeping bag?"
\par "Leave them."
\par "But won't we. . . ."
\par "I said leave them!"\~ There was wildness in his voice.
\par David backed up into the mine.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "I must discard hoquat things.\~ Come."
\par He turned to his right, went up around the mine shaft on a deer trail.\~ David darted into the open, followed.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "Follow close.\~ You will get wet.\~ Never mind that.\~ The climb will keep you warm."
\par They stayed on the deer trail until the sun began to break through the overcast.\~ Tiny cones like deer droppings covered the trail.\~ Ferns blanketed the ground on both sides.\~ Moss obscured all the downed trees.\~ The trail dipped and climbed.\~
 Water ran in the low spots.
\par As the sun came out, Katsuk took to the ferns and moss, climbing straight up a steep ridge side to another trail.\~ He turned right on this and soon they encountered snow on the ground.\~
 It had collected along the hill margins of the trail but had melted away on the downhill side.\~ They walked the thin strip of open ground.\~ Urine-colored lichen poked through the snow in the thinner places.
\par Once, they heard an aircraft flying low under the broken clouds.\~ It could not be seen through the heavy tree cover.
\par As they climbed, the trees began to thin.\~ The deer track crossed a park trail with a signboard.\~ The sign pointed left:\~ KIMTA PEAK.
\par Katsuk turned right.
\par They began encountering long stretches of snow on the trail.\~ There were old footprints in the snow.\~ The flat inner surfaces of the prints had almost lost their foot shape.\~ Rain pocked the prints.\~ Some of them showed mud stains.
\par Once, Katsuk pointed to the prints, said:\~ "They were going over Kimta Peak.\~ It was last week."
\par David studied the tracks.\~ He couldn't tell toe from heel.\~ "How do you know?"
\par "Do you see how we leave mud in the snow?\~ It is always after we cross open ground.\~ They left mud on the downhill side.\~ The tracks have melted for at least a week."
\par "Who was it, do you suppose?"
\par "Hoquat searching for us, perhaps."
\par David shivered as the wind gusted.\~ The air carried the chill of snow and ice.\~ Even the effort of keeping up with Katsuk failed to warm him.\~ He wondered how Katsuk could endure it in only loincloth and moccasins.\~ The moccasins were dark with water.
\~ The loincloth appeared soggy.\~ David's tennis shoes sloshed with each step.\~ His feet were numb with cold.
\par They came to another sign:\~ THREE PRUNE SHELTER.\~ It pointed downhill to the right.
\par Katsuk left the park trail there, took to a deer path that went straight up the hill.\~ David was pressed to keep up.
\par Whenever he could see up through the trees, the sky showed blue patches.\~ David prayed they would come out into warm sunshine.\~ The backs of his hands were wet and cold.\~ He tried to put them into his jacket pockets, but the jacket was soaking.
\par They came to a rocky ridgetop.\~ Katsuk followed it, climbing toward a mountain which lifted itself against clouds directly ahead.\~ Trees on both sides of the ridge were gnarled, stunted, wind-bent.\~ Wrinkled patches of lichen marked the rocks.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "We are near timberline.\~ We will go down soon."
\par He spoke above the sound of water roaring in a deep gorge to the right.\~ They came to an elk trail which angled down toward the sound.\~ Katsuk scrambled down onto the elk trail.\~ David followed, slipping, avoiding snow where he could.\~
 Katsuk was covering the ground in great long strides.\~ David ran to catch up, almost overran Katsuk.\~ An outthrust arm stopped him.
\par "Dangerous to run down such a hill," Katsuk said.\~ "You could run right off a cliff."
\par David nodded, shivered.\~ He felt the cold seep through him.\~ It was that way every time they stopped.\~ How could Katsuk stand it?
\par "Come," Katsuk said.
\par Again, they went down the trail.\~ Presently, they came out on a granite ledge above the river.\~ The roaring milky water below them filled the air with cold mist.\~ Katsuk turned left, upstream.\~
 Soon, the stunted trees gave way to tiny clumps of huckleberry bushes.\~ They encountered smaller and smaller bushes until there were none.\~ Lichen lay on the bare rocks.\~ Tufts of greenery speared through snow patches.\~
 The river became narrower, gray rocks thrusting out of it.\~ The sound of it was loud beside them.\~ The water was gray-green with snowmelt, no more than six feet across.\~ Patches of vapor drifted on its surface.
\par Katsuk came to the place he had been seeking -- rocks like stepping stones across the river.\~ Water piled high against the upstream sides of the rocks.\~ He looked upstream.\~ There was the ice wall from which this tumbling water flowed.\~
 He stared at the cold, dirty-white fountainhead of all that water.\~ Ice . . . ice. . . .
\par The boy stood behind him, huddled up, shivering with the cold.\~ Katsuk glanced at Hoquat a moment, then peered down to the right where the river plunged into the trees -- far, far down there.\~ The sun came through the clouds.\~
 He saw a deep pool in the river's middle distance:\~ scintillant water, its current pulled taut against the deep unrest beneath.\~ He felt the river ceaselessly churning in its depth.\~ Who counted that water or cut it into bits?\~
 The water was bound together, one end connected to the other.
\par "Why're we waiting?" David asked.
\par Katsuk did not hear him.\~ He thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 All things start downstream from this place.\~ Here is the beginning.}{\insrsid8201588 
\par There were river spirits here.\~ The spirits permitted no leisure for this torrent of water or the torrent in his own breast.\~ Each would run until it broke its energy into other forms.\~ All was movement, energy, and currents -- never ceasing.
\par He found a deep, calming, enjoyment in this thought.\~ His mind had taken a leap, not asking why, but how?
\par }{\i\insrsid8201588 How?}{\insrsid8201588 
\par The spirits told him:\~ "Never ceasing, one energy into another."
\par "Come," he said, and crossed the stream, jumping from rock to rock.
\par The boy followed.
