\s15\ql \li0\ri0\sb100\sa100\sbauto1\saauto1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\ipgp1 \fs24\lang1049\langfe1049\cgrid\langnp1049\langfenp1049 {\insrsid8201588 \page 
"About thirty thousand years ago," Katsuk said, "a lava flow pushed its way out of a vent in the middle slope up there."\~ He hooked a thumb over his shoulder.\~ "Some of it fell out in great lumps which you stupid hoquat called Indian tears."
\par David peered up at the mountain, which he could see shining in the morning sun beyond a stand of hemlocks.\~ The mountain was a series of rock pillars.\~ Cloud shapes drifted over it.\~ There was an avalanche scar on a slope to the south.\~
 A river ran somewhere under that slope, but the sound of it lay hidden beneath the wind soughing in the trees.
\par "What time is it?" David asked.
\par "By hoquat time?"
\par "Yes."
\par Katsuk glanced over his shoulder at the sun.\~ "About ten o'clock.\~ Why?"
\par "You know what I'd be doing at home right now?"
\par Katsuk glanced at Hoquat, sensing the boy's need to talk.\~ Why not?\~ If Hoquat talked here, that would keep his spirit silent.\~ Katsuk nodded, asked:\~ "What would you be doing?"
\par "Taking my tennis lesson."
\par "Tennis lesson," Katsuk said.\~ He shook his head.
\par Katsuk squatted on the slope.\~ He held a length of brown-black obsidian in his left hand.\~ He steadied the obsidian on his thigh and chipped at it with a piece of flint.\~ The sound of chipping rang sharply in the clear, high air.\~
 It produced a pungent smell which David sniffed.
\par "Tennis lesson," Katsuk repeated.\~ He tried to imagine the boy as a grown man -- rich and pampered, a romper man first class in the playboy army.\~ No longer innocent.\~ Black and white dress uniform for night.\~ Black tie.\~
 A crew-cut, nightclub smoke-blower.\~ Or whatever would pass for that in his time of maturity.\~ It was a kindness to prevent that.\~ It was a kindness to preserve Hoquat's innocence forever.
\par "Then I'd go swimming in our pool," David said.
\par Katsuk asked:\~ "Do you want to swim in the river down there?"
\par "It's too cold.\~ Our pool is heated."
\par Katsuk sighed, went on chipping.\~ The obsidian was beginning to take shape.\~ It would be a knife soon.
\par For some time now, David had been trying to plumb his captor's mood.\~ There had been increasingly long silences between them while walking around the mountain slope.\~ It had taken a full day.\~ There were ten pebbles in David's pocket -- ten days.\~
 Katsuk's few responses during the long hike had been more and more moody, snappish, and short.\~ Katsuk was troubled by some new awareness.\~ Was Katsuk losing his spirit powers?
\par David did not allow himself to think yet of escape.\~ But if Katsuk's powers were weakening. . . .
\par A large chip flew off the obsidian.\~ Katsuk held it up, turned it, examining the shape.
\par "What're you making?"\~ David asked.
\par "A knife."
\par "But you've got . . . my knife."\~ David glanced at Katsuk's waist.\~ The Russell knife had been missing all during the walk around the mountain, but he had guessed it was in the deerhide pouch Katsuk wore.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "I need a special kind of knife."
\par "Why?"
\par "To make my bow."
\par David accepted this, then:\~ "Have you been here before?"
\par "Many times."
\par "Did you make knives here?"
\par "No.\~ I guided hoquat in here to find pretty rocks."
\par "Did they make knives out of the rocks?"
\par "I don't think so."
\par "How do you know what kind of rock will make a knife?"
\par "My people made knives from these rocks for thousands of years.\~ They used to come up here at least once a year -- before you hoquat came with steel.\~ You call this rock obsidian.\~ We call it black fire -- }{\i\insrsid8201588 klalepiah.}{
\insrsid8201588 
\par David fell silent.\~ Where was the Russell knife?\~ Would Katsuk give it back?
\par Katsuk had caught a rabbit and two small quail in snares during the night.\~ He had cleaned them with a sharp piece of the brown-black rock, cooked them in an earth oven heated by pitch balls.\~ The pitch had made a hot fire with almost no smoke.
\par David found a remnant of rabbit leg, sat down, and chewed on it while he watched Katsuk work.\~ The gray striking rock in Katsuk's right hand had one narrow end.\~ Katsuk struck sharply and steadily at the obsidian, using the narrow end of the flint.\~
 Sparks flew.\~ The sulfurous odor grew strong in the still air.
\par Presently, David summoned his courage, asked:\~ "Where's my knife?"
\par Katsuk thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Ahhh, the sly, clever hoquat!\~ }{\insrsid8201588 He said:\~ "I must make my bow in the ancient way.\~ Steel cannot touch this wood."
\par "Then where's my knife?"
\par "I threw it in the river."
\par Outraged, David hurled the gnawed rabbit bone to the ground, leaped to his feet.\~ "That was my knife!"
\par "Be still," Katsuk said.
\par "My father gave me that knife," David said, his voice tight with fury.\~ Angry tears began running down his cheeks.
\par Katsuk peered up at him, weighing the boy's passion.\~ "Could your father not buy you another knife?"
\par "That one was for my birthday!"\~ David shook tears off his cheeks.\~ "Why'd you have to throw it away?"
\par Katsuk looked at the obsidian and flint in his hands.
\par }{\i\insrsid8201588 A birthday gift, father to son:\~ a man's gift to a man.}{\insrsid8201588 
\par Katsuk experienced emptiness at the certainty that he would never have a son to receive the gift of manhood.\~ The obsidian felt heavy in his hand.\~ He knew he was experiencing self-pity and it angered him.
\par Why pity anyone?\~ There could be no reprieve.
\par "Damn you!" David raged.\~ "I hope your Cedar sickness kills you!"
\par Awareness blazed in Katsuk.\~ There lay the source of the curse!\~ The Innocent had found a spirit to work his curse.\~ Where had Hoquat found this spirit?\~ Had he received it from Tskanay?\~ Then, where had she found it?
\par Katsuk said:\~ "I was warned by Bee to throw away that steel knife."
\par "Stupid Bee!"
\par Katsuk jerked his chin up, glared at the boy.\~ "Careful what you say about Bee.\~ He might not let you live out this day!"
\par The glazed look of madness in Katsuk's eyes cooled David's anger.\~ He felt only the loss now.\~ The knife was gone, thrown into a river by this madman.\~ David tried to take a deep breath, but his chest pained him.\~ The knife would never be found again.
\~ He thought abruptly of the murdered hiker.\~ That knife had killed a man.\~ Was that why it had been thrown away?
\par Katsuk went back to his chipping.
\par David said:\~ "Are you sure you didn't hide my knife in that pouch?"
\par Katsuk put down obsidian and flint, opened the pouch, exposed the interior to the boy.
\par David pointed:\~ "What's that little package?'
\par "It's not your knife.\~ You can see I do not have the knife."
\par "I see."\~ Still angry.\~ "What's that package?"
\par Katsuk sealed the pouch, went back to chipping his obsidian.\~ "It is the down of sea ducks."
\par "Down?"
\par "The soft feathers."
\par "I know that.\~ Why do you carry a stupid thing like that?"
\par Katsuk noted how anger spoke in the boy, thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 The down is to sprinkle on your body when I have slain you.\~ }{\insrsid8201588 He said:\~ "It is part of my spirit medicine."
\par "Why'd your spirit tell you to throw away my knife?" David asked.
\par Katsuk thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 He is learning to ask the right questions.}{\insrsid8201588 
\par "Why?" the boy demanded.
\par "To save me," Katsuk whispered.
\par "What?"
\par "To save me!"
\par "You told Cally nothing can save you."
\par "But Cally does not know me."
\par "She's your aunt."
\par "No.\~ She had a nephew named Charles Hobuhet.\~ I am Katsuk."
\par And Katsuk wondered:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Why do I explain myself to my victim?\~ What is he doing that I must defend myself?\~ Is it the knife I threw away?\~ That was a link with his father, the father he had before he became Hoquat.\~ Yes.\~
 I threw away his past.\~ It is what those drunken loggers did to Janiktaht . . . and to me.}{\insrsid8201588 
\par "I'll bet you've never even been in a heated pool," David said.
\par Katsuk smiled.\~ Hoquat's anger darted here and there.\~ It was like a creature in a cage.\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Tennis lessons, a swimming pool.\~ }{\insrsid8201588 
Hoquat had lived a sheltered life, a life of preserved innocence in the fashion of his people.\~ Despite Tskanay, he remained in that delicate transition place:\~ part-man part-boy.\~ Innocent.
\par Sorrow permeated David.\~ His mouth felt dry.\~ His chest ached.\~ He felt tired, frustrated, lonely.\~ Why was crazy Katsuk making a stone knife?\~ Why was he }{\i\insrsid8201588 really }{\insrsid8201588 making it?\~ Had Katsuk lied?
\par David remembered reading that Aztecs had killed their sacrificial victims with stone knives.\~ Aztecs were Indians.\~ He shook his head.\~ Katsuk had promised.\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 "Unless you tell me to do it, I will not kill you."\~ }{\insrsid8201588 
The stone knife had another purpose.\~ Perhaps it was just to make the stupid bow.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "You are no longer angry with me?"
\par "No."\~ Still sullen.
\par "Good.\~ Anger blocks the mind.\~ Anger does not learn.\~ There is much for you to learn."
\par }{\i\insrsid8201588 Anger does not learn! }{\insrsid8201588 David thought.\~ He climbed deliberately close to Katsuk, went a short way up the slope, and sat down with his back against the bole of a hemlock.\~
 Bits of obsidian littered the ground around him.\~ He picked up a handful, began throwing them past Katsuk at brush and trees down the slope.
\par The bits of obsidian made a clattering sound when they hit a tree.\~ They went flick-flick in salal leaves on the forest floor.\~ It was a curious counterpoint noise to Katsuk's chipping.\~ David felt his anger pouring out in the exertion
 of throwing the rocks.\~ He threw harder, harder.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "If you wish to throw a rock at me, throw it.\~ Do not play games with your feelings."
\par David leaped up, anger flaring.\~ He held a sharp-edged piece of obsidian the size of a quail's egg in his hand.\~ He gritted his teeth, hurled the rock at Katsuk with all of his strength.\~
 The rock struck a glancing blow on Katsuk's cheek, left a red slash from which blood oozed.
\par Terrified by what he had done, David stepped backward.\~ Every muscle was in readiness to flee.
\par Katsuk put a finger to the wound, brought it away, examined the blood.\~ Curious.\~ The cut did not hurt.\~ What could it mean that such a blow caused no pain?\~ There had been a brief sensation of pressure, but no pain.\~ Ahhh, Bee had blocked off
 the pain.\~ Bee had interposed a magic to make the blow ineffective.\~ It was a message from Bee, The Innocent's spirit would not prevail.
\par "}{\i\insrsid8201588 I am Tamanawis speaking to you}{\insrsid8201588 . . . ."
\par David said:\~ "Katsuk?\~ Katsuk, I'm sorry."
\par Katsuk looked up at him.\~ Hoquat appeared ready for flight, his eyes wide and bright with fear.\~ Katsuk nodded, said:\~ "Now, you know a }{\i\insrsid8201588 little }{\insrsid8201588 of how I felt when I took you from the hoquat camp.\~
 What a hate that must be to want to kill an innocent for it.\~ Did you ever think of that?"
\par }{\i\insrsid8201588 Kill an innocent!\~ }{\insrsid8201588 David thought.\~ He said:\~ "But you promised. . . ."
\par "I will keep that promise.\~ It is the way of my people.\~ We do not tell hoquat lies.\~ Do you know how it is?"
\par "What?"
\par "When we were whalers, whale had to demand the harpoon.\~ Whale asked us to kill him."
\par "But I'd never. . . ."
\par "Then you are safe."
\par Katsuk returned to his chipping.
\par David ventured a step closer to Katsuk.\~ "Does it hurt?"
\par "Bee will not let it hurt.\~ Be quiet.\~ I must concentrate."
\par "But it's bleeding."
\par "The bleeding will stop."
\par "Shouldn't we put something on it?"
\par "It is a small wound.\~ Your mouth is a bigger wound.\~ Be quiet or I will put something in your mouth."
\par David gulped, wiped his mouth with the back of his hand.\~ He found it difficult not to look at the dark scratch on Katsuk's cheek.\~ The bleeding stopped, but coagulation formed a ragged lower edge to the wound.
\par Why didn't it hurt?
\par It outraged David that the wound did not hurt.\~ He had wanted it to hurt.\~ Cuts always hurt.\~ But Katsuk had spirit protectors.\~ Maybe it really didn't hurt.
\par David turned his attention to the obsidian knife taking shape under Katsuk's hands.\~ The blade, about four inches long and sharply wedged, was held flat against Katsuk's thigh.\~ With quick, glancing blows, Katsuk broke tiny flakes from the edges.
\par The knife did not appear long or slim enough to stab anyone.\~ The cutting edges were serrated.\~ But it could cut an artery.\~ He thought again of the hiker Katsuk had killed.\~ That hiker had not asked to be killed.\~ But Katsuk had murdered him anyway.

\par David found his mouth suddenly dry.\~ He said:\~ "That guy . . . you know, on the trail . . . the guy you . . . well, he didn't ask you to. . . ."
\par "You hoquat always think mouth-talk is the only talk."\~ Katsuk spoke without looking up from his work.\~ "Why can't you learn body-talk?\~ When Raven made you, did he leave that ability out of you?"
\par "What's body-talk?"
\par "It is what you do.\~ A thing you do can say something about what you want."
\par "That's crazy talk about Raven."
\par "God made us, eh?"
\par "Yes!"
\par "It depends on what you're taught, I guess."
\par "Well, I don't believe that about body-talk and Raven."
\par "You don't believe Raven keeps you tied to me?"
\par David could not answer.\~ Raven }{\i\insrsid8201588 did do }{\insrsid8201588 what Katsuk wanted.\~ The birds went where Katsuk ordered them to go.\~ To know where the birds would go -- what a power that was.
\par Katsuk said:\~ "You are quiet.\~ Did Raven take your tongue?\~ Raven can do that.\~ Your stupid hoquat world does not prepare you to deal with Raven."
\par "You always say }{\i\insrsid8201588 stupid }{\insrsid8201588 when you talk about my people," David accused.\~ "Isn't there anything good about our world?"
\par "Our world?" Katsuk asked.\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 "Your }{\insrsid8201588 world, Hoquat."
\par "But nothing good in it?"
\par "I see only death in it.\~ The whole world dies of you."
\par "What about our doctors?\~ We have better doctors than you ever had."
\par "Your doctors are tied to illness and death.\~ They make as much illness and death as they cure.\~ An exact balance.\~ It's called a transactional relationship.\~ But they are so blind, they do not see how they are tied to what they do."
\par "Transactional . . . relationship?\~ What's that?"
\par "A transaction is where you trade one thing for another.\~ When you buy something, that's a transaction."
\par "Ahh, that's just big words that don't mean anything."
\par "They are words from your world, Hoquat."
\par "But they don't mean anything."
\par "They mean doctors don't know they do it, but still they do it:\~ They maintain a level of illness to justify their existence.\~ Police do the same thing with crime.\~ Lawyers keep up the legal confusions.\~ Body-talk, Hoquat.\~
 No matter what they say they want, or how hard they work to overcome their defects, things work out in a way that keeps them busy and justifies their existence."
\par "That's crazy!"
\par "Yes, it is crazy, but it is real.\~ It is what you see when you understand body-talk."
\par "But my world does lots of good things.\~ People don't go hungry anymore."
\par "But they do, Hoquat.\~ In Asia, they --"
\par "I mean people in this country."
\par "Aren't they }{\i\insrsid8201588 people }{\insrsid8201588 in the other countries?"
\par "Sure, but. . . ."
\par "Even in this country -- in the mountains of your East, in the South, in big cities, people are hungry.\~ People die of hunger every year.\~ Old people, young people.\~ My people die that way, too, because they try to live like hoquat.\~
 And the world gets hungrier and hungrier. . . ."
\par "What about our houses?\~ We build better houses than you ever saw."
\par "And you destroy the earth to plunge your houses into it.\~ You build where no house should be.\~ You are insensitives.\~ You live }{\i\insrsid8201588 against }{\insrsid8201588 the earth, not }{\i\insrsid8201588 with }{\insrsid8201588 it."
\par "We have cars!"
\par "And your cars are smothering you."
\par David quested in his mind for something Katsuk could not strike down.\~ Music?\~ He'd sneer the way adults always did.\~ Education?\~ He'd say it didn't prepare you to live out here.\~ Science?\~ He'd say it was killing the worl
d with big bombs, big machines.
\par "Katsuk, what do you mean by body-talk?"
\par "What your actions say.\~ You say with your mouth:\~ 'That's too bad.'\~ Then you laugh.\~ That means you're really happy while you're saying you're sorry.\~ You say:\~ 'I love you.'\~ Then you do something to hurt that person's feelings.\~
 Body-talk is what you }{\i\insrsid8201588 do.\~ }{\insrsid8201588 If you say, 'I don't want that to happen,' and all the while you are making it happen, which thing are we to believe?\~ Do we believe the words or do we believe the body?"
\par David thought about words.\~ He thought about church and sermons, of all the words about "eternal life."\~ Were the words true, or did the preacher's body say something different?
\par "Katsuk, do your people understand body-talk?"
\par "Some of them.\~ The old ones did.\~ Our language tells me this."
\par "How?"
\par "We say eat while eating, shit while shitting, fuck while fucking.\~ The words and the body agree."
\par "That's just dirty talk."
\par "It is innocent talk, Hoquat.\~ Innocent."
\par }\pard \s15\qc \li0\ri0\sb100\sa100\sbauto1\saauto1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\ipgp1 {\insrsid8201588 * * *
