\s15\ql \li0\ri0\sb100\sa100\sbauto1\saauto1\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\ipgp1 \fs24\lang1049\langfe1049\cgrid\langnp1049\langfenp1049 {\insrsid8201588 \page 
Katsuk lay on moss between two logs, his mind howling in a fevered nightmare.\~ There was a wood path, an arrow.\~ The arrow must balance just right.\~ He had found the wood for the arrow in the avalanche scar of a tall cedar.\~ 
It had been a trick, all a trick.\~ He held the arrow and the arrow held him.\~ He led a cortege up the wood path from the most ancient times to the present.\~ His mind was drunk with all the lives it held.
\par A spirit shouted in his mind:\~ "The earth does not know who owns it!"
\par Katsuk groaned.
\par Delirium moved his feet on the wood path.\~ He sang the names of his dead, but each new name brought a change in the nightmare.\~ When he sang Janiktaht's name, he saw Hoquat running, hair flying like a wind-whipped bush.
\par Another name:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Okhoots.}{\insrsid8201588 
\par He was in a field embroidered with yellow flowers, a bubbling spring beside the field.\~ He drank at the spring, but the water failed to slake the dry burning of his throat.
\par Another name:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Grandfather Hobuhet.}{\insrsid8201588 
\par He was confronted by wave tops blown white in a gale, a sorrel weaving in green water.\~ A dead whale rose out of the water, said:\~ "You dare disturb me!"
\par Another name:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Tskuldik.}{\insrsid8201588 
\par }{\i\insrsid8201588 Father . . . father . . . father!}{\insrsid8201588 
\par He called a nameless name in a canyon, was back on the nightmare trail of his ordeal.\~ He heard the woods' dirge, felt wet bracken at his waist.\~ He was marching upcountry from the hoquat places.\~
 There was a dirty yellow logging rig parked beside the road, heavy green of second-growth fir behind it.\~ Side roads poked out into the tree wall.\~ Dead snags thrust up through the green.
\par There was an alder bottom, a stump ranch glimpsed through the bleached-white maze of trunks.\~ He saw platform notches on old stumps, ragged bark dangling.\~ There was a corrugated culvert with ars
enic-yellow skunk cabbages on one side of a rutted road, water trickling out the other side.\~ He saw the open scar of a logged-off hillside, a sign:\~ WARNING:\~ UNDERGROUND POWER AND TELEPHONE CABLES.
\par As he read the sign, Katsuk felt his mind plunge into a cold river.\~ He saw moss-covered boughs vibrating in the water.\~ He became one of the boughs.
\par He thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 I have become a water spirit.}{\insrsid8201588 
\par In his delirium, he screamed for Raven to save him.\~ Raven swam by him under the water, became a fish, }{\i\insrsid8201588 kull t'kope!}{\insrsid8201588 
\par Katsuk awoke, trembling with terror.\~ Cramps contorted his body.\~ He felt weak, drained.\~ Dawnlight glared gray through the shelter's open entrance.\~ Sweat bathed him.\~ He shivered with chill.\~
 Blankets had been tucked around him, but he had thrown them off in his nightmare thrashing.
\par Painfully, his knees trembling with Cedar sickness, he managed to stand, forced himself to the entrance.\~ He leaned against a log upright, shivered, half conscious of some ultimate necessity which he could not name.
\par Where was Hoquat?
\par A piece of wood broke with a clear snapping off to his right.\~ The boy came around the shelter there, his arms loaded with firewood.\~ He dumped the wood beside the gray ashes of the fire pit.
\par Katsuk stared at the boy, at the fire pit, trying to put the two together in his thoughts.
\par David saw the weakness in Katsuk, said:\~ "I found a can of beans in that little barrel and heated them.\~ I left most of them for you."
\par He used a split length of green wood to lift the can from the ashes and place it at Katsuk's feet.\~ A flat piece of wood for a spoon protruded from the can.
\par Katsuk squatted, ate greedily, hungry for the warmth more than for the food.\~ The beans tasted of ashes.\~ They burned his tongue, but he gulped them, felt heat radiate from his stomach.
\par The boy, working to restore the fire, said:\~ "You had a nightmare.\~ You yelled and tossed around all night.\~ I kept the fire going most of the night."
\par Flame began to climb through the wood the boy had placed in the coals beneath the ashes.
\par Katsuk nodded dumbly.\~ He heard water dashing on stones only a few steps from the shelter but could not find the strength to go to it.\~ A burning dryness filled his throat.
\par "Wa-ter," he croaked.
\par The boy stood up from the fire, took the empty bean can to the river.
\par The way the leaf-broken sunlight dappled the boy's hair made Katsuk think of a lion he had seen in a zoo:\~ a lion draped in sunlight and shadows.\~ The memory caged him.\~ He thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Does Hoquat have a new spirit?\~ Is it Lion?\~
 I do not know that spirit.}{\insrsid8201588 
\par David returned from the river with the can slopping icy water.\~ He saw the glazed look in Katsuk's eyes.\~ Katsuk clutched the can with both hands, drained it, said:\~ "More."
\par The boy brought another can of water.\~ Katsuk drank it.
\par A distant engine sound came into the valley, rising above the noise of the river.\~ It grew louder:\~ a plane flying low over the ridge above them.\~ The sound went away upcountry.
\par David stood, stared through the trees, hoping for a glimpse of the aircraft.\~ He failed to see it.
\par Katsuk ignored the sound.\~ He seemed to have lapsed back into his dream-sleep, squatting in the shelter's doorway, occasionally shuddering.
\par David put more wood on the fire, piled rocks around the flames to heat them.\~ He said:\~ "It's going to rain again."
\par Katsuk stared through slitted eyes at the boy.\~ He thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 The victim is here, but he must desire my arrow.\~ The Innocent must ask for death.}{\insrsid8201588 
\par Low-voiced in the ancient tongue, Katsuk began chanting:
\par }{\i\insrsid8201588 "Your body will accept the consecrated arrow.\~ Pride will fill your soul at the touch of my sharp and biting point.\~ Your soul will turn toward the sun and people will say to one another:\~ 'How proudly he died!'\~
 Ravens will alight beside your body, but they will not touch your flesh.\~ Your pride will send you outward from your body.\~ You will become a great bird and fly from one end of the world to the other.\~ This is how you will accept the arrow."}{
\insrsid8201588 
\par David listened until the low chanting stopped, said:\~ "There are more beans in that barrel.\~ Do you want some?"
\par "Why do you not run away?" Katsuk asked.\~ "You have given me the Cedar sickness.\~ I could not stop you."
\par The boy shrugged, said:\~ "You're sick."
\par Katsuk felt at his waist for the obsidian knife.\~ It was gone!\~ He stared around him, wild-eyed.\~ His pouch with the consecrated down to place on the sacrificed body -- that, too, was gone.\~
 Katsuk lurched to his feet, clutching at the boy, fell heavily beside the fire pit.
\par David jumped up, then hurried to kneel beside Katsuk.
\par "Knife," Katsuk whispered.
\par "Your knife?\~ I was afraid you'd cut yourself tossing around on it.\~ I hung the knife and your pouch in the corner back there where you put the bow and arrow."\~ He gestured into the shelter.
\par Katsuk tried to turn his head, but his neck ached.
\par David put an arm under Katsuk's shoulders, said:\~ "You should be in the bed.\~ I'm heating rocks.\~ Come on."\~ He helped Katsuk back to the moss between the logs, pulled the blankets over him.
\par Katsuk allowed himself to be tucked into the blankets, asked:\~ "Why do you help me?\~ It was you who put the sickness on me."
\par "That's crazy."
\par "It is not!\~ I know you did it.\~ I saw you in my dream.\~ You put it into these blankets."
\par "Those are }{\i\insrsid8201588 your }{\insrsid8201588 blankets!\~ You took them out of that barrel!"
\par "You could have changed the blankets.\~ You hoquat have used sickness blankets on us before.\~ You gave us the smallpox with your blankets.\~ You killed us with hoquat sickness.\~ Why do you do this to me?"
\par "Do you want more beans or don't you?"
\par "Hoquat, I have had my death dream.\~ I have dreamed the way it will be."
\par "That's crazy talk."
\par "No!\~ I have dreamed it.\~ I will go into the sea and become a fish.\~ You hoquat will catch me."
\par The boy shook his head, went back to the fire.\~ He put more wood on it, felt the outsides of the rocks around the flames.
\par It grew suddenly dark under the trees and began to rain.\~ Cold wind blew up the river canyon.\~ It drove big wet droplets before it, drummed rain into the trees and onto the mossy roof of the shelter.\~
 Water ran from the eaves and blew in across the fire.\~ It hissed on the rocks.
\par Katsuk felt a nightmare take him.\~ He tried to scream but could make no sound.\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Water Baby has me! }{\insrsid8201588 he thought.\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 How did it learn my name?}{\insrsid8201588 
\par After what seemed only a few seconds, Katsuk awoke to find warm stones piled on the blankets around his feet.\~ A smell of scorched wool drifted on the damp air.\~ Rain still fell from a dark sky.
\par The boy came then, replaced a stone on the blankets.\~ He used a bent green limb of alder to handle the stone.\~ Katsuk felt the warmth.
\par "You've been asleep all day," the boy said.\~ "Are you hungry?\~ I heated more beans."
\par Katsuk's head felt light.\~ His throat was a dry patch of sand.\~ He could only nod and croak.
\par The boy brought him a can of water.\~ Katsuk drank it greedily, then permitted himself to be fed.\~ He opened his mouth like a bird for each bite.
\par "More water?"
\par "Yes."
\par The boy brought it.\~ Katsuk drank, fell back.
\par "More?"
\par "No."
\par Katsuk felt himself returning to the middle of his own being, but it was all wrong.\~ It was himself where he had come into this primitive world, but pieces had been snipped away, the lines changed.\~
 If he could see his own face in a mirror, he knew it would be unfamiliar.\~ He might reject that face.\~ The eyes would be those of a stranger.\~ He longed for restful sleep but felt nightmares lurking.\~
 The spirits waited with their willy-nilly purpose, unreasonable and demanding.\~ He tipped his head back, stretching his neck.\~ His mind rang like a bell.
\par He thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 l am being overwhelmed by the spirits!}{\insrsid8201588 
\par The boy came with a can of water.\~ Katsuk lifted his head to drink.\~ Part of the water spilled down his chin.\~ He lay back.\~ The drink weighed on him, made his body torpid.
\par Katsuk thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 He has poisoned me!}{\insrsid8201588 
\par The rain beat on the roof over him, a drum sound, whispering at first, then louder.\~ He thought he heard a flute with the drum:\~ pitiful music but marvelous.\~ His life danced on the flute song, a summer moth, about to die.
\par }{\i\insrsid8201588 I have become the soul of this place, }{\insrsid8201588 he thought.\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Why has Soul Catcher brought me here?}{\insrsid8201588 
\par He awoke in darkness.\~ The silence was resonant, the silence after a drum.\~ The rain had stopped.\~ Faint, unrhythmic drips came from the eaves.\~ The fire had burned low.\~
 A shadow near the fire revealed itself as the boy asleep curled up beside the warm rocks.\~ As Katsuk stirred, the boy sat up, stared into the shelter's darkness.
\par "Katsuk?"
\par "I am here."
\par "How do you feel?"
\par Katsuk felt the clarity in his head.\~ Cedar sickness had left him.\~ He sensed his weakness, but the dry juice of his fear had been squeezed into oblivion.
\par "The sickness has gone from me," Katsuk said.
\par "Are you thirsty?"
\par "Yes."
\par The boy brought a can of water.\~ Katsuk drank it, his hand steady.
\par "More?"
\par "No."
\par Katsuk sensed the multiplicity of his universe, knew the spirits remained within him.\~ He said:\~ "You drove the sickness from my body, Hoquat.\~ Why?"
\par "I couldn't just leave you.\~ You were sick."
\par "I was sick, yes."
\par "May I come in there now and sleep under the blankets?"
\par "You are cold?"
\par "Yes."
\par "It is warm here."\~ Katsuk opened the blankets.
\par The boy scrambled over the logs that contained the moss bed, crawled under the blankets.\~ Katsuk felt the thin body trembling.
\par Presently, Katsuk said:\~ "Nothing has changed, Hoquat."
\par "What?"
\par "I still must create a holy obscenity."
\par "Go to sleep, Katsuk."\~ The boy sounded exhausted.
\par "We have been gone thirteen nights," Katsuk said.
\par The boy made no response.\~ His trembling had stilled.\~ Soft, even breathing betrayed sleep.
\par Katsuk thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Nothing has changed.\~ I must produce for this world a nightmare they will dream while awake.}{\insrsid8201588 
