\~ It was several heartbeats before he realized he was staring at the moon, another arc of it eaten away by Beaver.\~ It was cold.\~ A moon river glowed through the trees outside the shelter.\~
 The river whispered to him, reminding him of rain and silence.\~ A mountain slowly revealed itself through the trees.\~ It had been there all along, but now it showed itself to him:\~ moon-drenched, awash with snow.\~ A star mantle woun
d through the sky beyond the mountain.
\par With sudden shock, David realized Katsuk was not beside him.
\par "Katsuk?" he ventured, voice low.
\par No answer.
\par Katsuk had added more wood to the fire.\~ Coals glowed brightly in the fire pit.
\par David pulled the blankets more tightly around himself.\~ Smoke from the fire pit blurred the moon's pale witchery.\~ The sky was full of stars!\~ He recalled Katsuk saying the stars were holes in a black deerhide.\~ Crazy Katsuk!\~ Where was he?
\par Katsuk had prayed:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Net of stars, Deer and Bear in the sky}{\insrsid8201588  -- I }{\i\insrsid8201588 take care for thee!}{\insrsid8201588 
\par }{\i\insrsid8201588 "The moon is the eye of Kwahoutze!"}{\insrsid8201588 
\par Again, David called:\~ "Katsuk?"
\par But there was no answer to the call -- only the wind in the trees, the voices of the river.
\par David peered into the darkness, searching.\~ Where was Katsuk?
\par In the remembered green of the night, a shadow moved.\~ Katsuk stood beside the fire pit, flung there by his own movement.
\par "I am here, Hoquat."
\par Katsuk stared into the shelter's blackness, seeing the boy there and not seeing him.\~ It was as though he stared at the boy's dream and the spirit talking:
\par }{\i\insrsid8201588 "You are not yet ready.\~ When you are ready, I will come for you.\~ Pray then, and a wish will be granted you."}{\insrsid8201588 
\par Those were the spirit's words.
\par David asked:\~ "Where have you been?"\~ He said it accusingly, aware of a change in Katsuk's manner, but unable to identify that change.
\par Katsuk heard the question like a voice calling within his skull and wondered:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Should I tell him where I've been?\~ Is that what the spirit demands of me now?}{\insrsid8201588 
\par The question disturbed Katsuk, setting up currents within him that left his mind in turmoil.\~ He recalled how Raven had awakened him in the night, speaking from a dream that bridged the two worlds.\~
 Raven had ordered him to go downstream to the big meadow, warning him of danger there.\~ Searchers were camped there now, a big party of them with tents and rifles and radios.
\par Katsuk recalled his stalking approach to the camp.\~ He had crawled through the tall grass to within a few yards of the searchers, close enough to hear the men awakening in the dark and preparing for their day of hunting for human quarry.\~
 Their mouths full of sleep, the men had talked.\~ Their words had revealed much.\~ The smoke from the fire in the abandoned shelter on Sam's River had been seen by an aircraft searcher just before dark last night.\~
 Could Hoquat be blamed for building up that fire?\~ Had it been a breach of innocence?\~ Katsuk thought not.\~ The boy had been concerned with his captor's illness and with the need for warmth.
\par With that fire as their goal, though, the men from the meadow would be here soon.\~ Even now, they could be in the hills around the shelter, waiting for dawn before moving.
\par "Where were you?" the boy pressed.
\par "I've been walking in my forest."
\par David sensed evasion in the answer, asked:\~ "Will it be dawn soon?"
\par "Yes."
\par "Why did you go walking, Katsuk?"
\par "Raven called me."
\par David heard the remoteness in Katsuk's voice, realized the man stood half in the spirit world, in the place of his dreams and his visions.
\par "Are we going to stay here today?" David asked.
\par "We are going to stay."
\par "Good.\~ You should rest after your sickness."
\par And David thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Maybe if I just talk to him calmly he'll come out of it and be all right.}{\insrsid8201588 
\par Katsuk sensed then that the boy had also developed another self which must be reasoned with, influenced, and understood.\~ The immobility in the surface of this youth was not to be mistaken for peace.\~ Hoquat's spirit was no longer hiding.\~
 And Katsuk asked himself:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Why shouldn't this happen to Hoquat as it happened to me?}{\insrsid8201588 
\par Why else had Hoquat nursed his captor through the Cedar sickness?\~ Logic said the boy should flee while Katsuk was weak, yet he stayed.
\par David felt the pressure of Katsuk's silence, asked:\~ "Do you need anything?\~ Shall I get up now?"
\par Katsuk hesitated, then:\~ "There is no need for you to get up.\~ We have a little time left us yet."
\par Katsuk thought then of the bow and its single arrow hidden in a tree behind him.\~ The past and the present were tied together, but the great circle had yet to be completed.\~
 He felt the pouch at his waist, the packet with the down from sea ducks in it to scatter on the slain victim as it had been done through all time.\~ He knew his mind grazed above its old levels.\~ He sensed Soul Catcher speaking to him and through him.\~
 The passionate simplicity of Bee had caught him up in full awareness of death and world-silence.\~ The spirit power of his realization reached all through him.\~ He felt death not as negation but as the assignment of his life.\~ It was why he sto
od in this place.\~ It was why he had made the bow, touching the wood only with a stone knife.\~ It was why he had fitted the old arrowhead from the ocean beach into its new wooden pocket, preparing it for the death to come.
\par Spirits had energized him.\~ They were spirits without shape or smell or sound -- yet they moved this world.\~ They moved it!\~ They moved the men in the river meadow.\~ They moved the aircraft and machines engaged in this primitive contest.\~
 They moved the Innocent who must die.\~ They moved Katsuk, who had become more spirit than man.
\par Katsuk thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 I must do this thing to the perfection which the old gods have ordered, It must have the unmistakable spirit pattern that all men may understand it:\~ good and evil bound one to the other by unbr
eakable form, the circle completed.\~ I must keep faith with my past.\~ Goodevil!\~ One thing.\~ That is what I do.}{\insrsid8201588 
\par With inward vision, he sensed elk horn lances in the dark all around him.\~ Their shafts were trimmed with tufted bear fur.\~ They were held by people from the past.\~ Those people came from the time when men had lived with the land and not against it.\~
 He dropped his gaze to his hand.\~ The shape of it was there, but details were lost in shadow.\~ Memory provided the image:\~ Bee's slug-white accusation in his skin.
\par Katsuk thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Any man may emulate the bee.\~ A man may sting the entire universe if he does it properly.\~ He must only find the right nerve to receive his barb.\~
 It must be an evil thing I do, with the good visible only when they turn it over.\~ The shape of hate must be revealed in it, and betrayal and anguish and the insanities we all share.\~ Only later should they see the love.}{\insrsid8201588 
\par David sensed undercurrents in the silence.\~ He found himself afraid }{\i\insrsid8201588 for }{\insrsid8201588 Katsuk and }{\i\insrsid8201588 of }{\insrsid8201588 him.\~ The man had become o
nce more that wild creature who had bound his captive's arms and half dragged him to the cave a night's march from Six Rivers Camp.
\par }{\i\insrsid8201588 What's he thinking now? }{\insrsid8201588 David wondered.\~ And he said:\~ "Katsuk, shouldn't you come back to bed?"
\par Katsuk heard two questions in the boy's words, one on the surface and one beneath.\~ The second question asked:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 "What can I do to help you?"}{\insrsid8201588 
\par "Do not worry about me, Hoquat," Katsuk said.\~ "It is well with me."
\par David heard a softness in Katsuk's voice.\~ Sleep lay at the edge of the boy's awareness like a gray cloud.\~ Katsuk was concerned for his captive now.\~ The boy readjusted the blankets around him, shifted closer to the coals in the fire pit.\~
 The night was cold.
\par Katsuk heard the movement as a demonstration of life.\~ He thought in sudden fearful awareness of the thing he had to do in this world of flesh and time.\~ Would people misinterpret his actions?
\par The spirits had summoned him to perform an artistic act.\~ It would be a refinement of blood revenge, a supreme example to be appreciated by this entire world.\~ His own people would understand this much of it.\~
 His own people had blood revenge locked into their history.\~ They would be stirred in their innermost being.\~ They would recognize why it had been done in the ancient way -- a m
ark upon raw earth, an incantation, a bow untouched by steel, a death arrow with a stone head, the down of sea ducks sprinkled upon the victim.\~ They would see the circle and this would lead them to the other meanings within this act.
\par What of the hoquat, though?\~ Their primitive times lay farther back, although they were more violent.\~ They had hidden their own violence from their surface awareness and might not recognize Katsuk's ritual.\~
 Realization would seep upward from the spirit side, though.\~ The very nature of the Innocent's death could not be denied.
\par "I have in truth become Soul Catcher," Katsuk said, realizing he had spoken aloud only after the words were uttered.
\par "What'd you say?"\~ The boy's voice was heavy with sleep.
\par "I am the creature of spirits."
\par "Are you sick again, Katsuk?"\~ The boy was coming back from sleep, his tone worried.
\par "I no longer have the Cedar sickness, Hoquat."
\par His flesh gripped by anguish, Katsuk thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Only one thing remains.\~ The Innocent must ask me for the arrow.\~ He must show that he is ready.\~ He must give me his spirit wish.}{\insrsid8201588 
\par Silently, Katsuk prayed:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 "O, Life Giver, now that you have seen the way a part of your all-powerful being goes, put all of you that way.\~ Bring the circle to completion."}{\insrsid8201588 
\par Somewhere down the river behind Katsuk, a man shouted.\~ It was a hoarse sound, words unintelligible but full of menace.
\par David started from sleep.\~ "What was that?"
\par Katsuk did not turn toward the sound.\~ He thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 It must be decided now.\~ }{\insrsid8201588 He said:\~ "The searchers have found us."
\par "People coming?"
\par "Your people are coming, Hoquat."
\par "Are you sure?"
\par "I am sure.\~ That was where I went walking in my forest, Hoquat.\~ I went down to the meadow.\~ There was a camp in the meadow.\~ The people from that camp will be here by daylight."
\par David heard the words with mounting panic.\~ "What're we going to do?"
\par "We?"
\par "You've gotta run, Katsuk!"\~ Even as he spoke, David felt the mixture of reason and unreason in his words.\~ But the demand for flight was larger than any other consideration.
\par "Why must we run?" Katsuk asked.\~ He sensed the spirit guiding the boy's reason through a maze of panic.
\par "You can't let them catch you!"
\par Katsuk spoke with the calming presence of his vision:\~ "Where would I run?\~ I am still weak from the Cedar sickness.\~ I could not go far."
\par David dropped the blankets from his shoulders, jumped up.\~ The man's serenity outraged him.\~ "I'll help you!"
\par "Why would you help me?"
\par "Because . . . because they. . . ."
\par "Because they will kill me?"
\par }{\i\insrsid8201588 How could the man be so calm?\~ }{\insrsid8201588 David asked himself.\~ And he blurted:\~ "Katsuk!\~ You've gotta run!"
\par "I cannot."
\par "You've just gotta!"\~ The boy clutched up the blankets, thrust them across the glowing fire pit at Katsuk.\~ "Here!\~ Take the blankets and go hide on the hill.\~ There must be someplace to hide up there.\~ I'll tell 'em you left yesterday."
\par "Why would you do such a thing?"
\par Katsuk's patience filled David with panic.\~ He said:\~ "Because I don't want you caught . . . and put in jail."
\par "Hoquat, Hoquat," Katsuk reasoned, "until these past few weeks I've lived all my life in cages."
\par The boy was frantic now.\~ "They'll put you in jail!"
\par "No.\~ They will kill me."
\par David immediately saw the logic of this.\~ Katsuk had murdered a man.\~ David said:\~ "I won't tell them about that guy."
\par "What . . . guy?"
\par "You know!\~ The hiker, the guy you . . .\~ You know!"\~ How could Katsuk be this stupid?
\par "But they will kill me because I kidnapped you."
\par "I'll tell 'em I came of my own free will."
\par "Did you?"
\par "Yes!"
\par Katsuk thought:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 Now, the spirits guide us both.\~ The }{\insrsid8201588 Innocent had not yet asked for the consecrated arrow.\~ He was not yet ready.\~ But the circle was closing.\~ Katsuk said:\~ "But what about my message?"
\par "What message?"\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 There he went, talking crazy again!}{\insrsid8201588 
\par "The spirit message I must send to the whole world," Katsuk explained.
\par "I don't care about your message!\~ Send it!\~ Just don't let them catch you!"
\par Katsuk nodded.\~ Thus it went.\~ He said:\~ "Then it is your wish -- your }{\i\insrsid8201588 spirit }{\insrsid8201588 wish, that I send my message?"
\par "Yes!\~ Only hurry.\~ I can hear them coming."
\par Katsuk sensed the calmness of his vision sweep upward through his body from the soles of his feet.\~ He spoke formally, as one did to the properly prepared sacrificial victim.\~ "Very well, Hoquat.\~ I admire your courage, your beauty, and your innocence.
\~ You are admirable.\~ Let no man doubt that.\~ Let all men and all spirits. . . ."
\par "Hurry, Katsuk," David whispered.\~ "Hurry."
\par "Let all men and all spirits," Katsuk repeated, "learn of your qualities, Hoquat.\~ Please sit down and wait here.\~ I will go now."
\par With a sigh of relief, the boy sank to a sitting position on one of the bed logs beside the shelter's entrance.\~ "Hurry," he whispered.\~ "They're close.\~ I can hear them."
\par Katsuk cocked his head to listen.\~ Yes, there were voices shouting directions in the dark, a movement seen only by its noises.\~ Still in the formal tone, he said:\~ "Hoquat, your friend Katsuk bids you good-bye."
\par "Good-bye, Katsuk," the boy whispered.
\par Quickly now, because he could feel the predawn stillness in the air and see the flashlights of searchers coming through the trees across the river, Katsuk faded back in the shadows to the young spruce where he had secreted the bow and arrow.\~
 Murmuring his prayers, he set the bowstring, that hard line of walrus gut.\~ The bow trembled in his hands, then steadied as he felt the power of it.\~ Truly, it was a god-bow.\~ He nocked the arrow against the bowstring.\~
 Now, his vision focused down to the infinity of this instant.
\par A bird whistled in the trees overhead.
\par Katsuk nodded his awareness.\~ The animals of this forest knew the moment had come.\~ He felt the spirit power surge all through his muscles.\~
 He turned toward the shelter, sensed the morning world begin to glow all around him, all platinum and gray movement.\~ The boy could be seen behind the fire pit, sitting wrapped in a blanket, head bowed, a primordial figure lost to the world of flesh.

\par Although he heard no sound of it, Katsuk knew the boy was crying.\~ Hoquat was shedding spirit tears for this world.
\par Steadily, Katsuk drew the bow taut, sighted as his grandfather had taught him.\~ His thumb felt the fletching of the arrow.\~ His fingers held the unpolished cedar of the arrow.\~
 All of his senses were concentrated upon this moment -- river, wind, forest, boy, Katsuk . . . all one.\~ In the magic instant, feeling the bow become part of his own flesh, Katsuk released the arrow.\~ He heard the }{\i\insrsid8201588 whang }{
\insrsid8201588 of the walrus gut.\~ The sound flew straight across the clearing with the arrow.\~ Straight it went and into the boy's chest.
\par Hoquat jerked once against the log post at the shelter's entrance.\~ The post held him upright.\~ He did not move again.
\par For David, there was only the sharp and crashing instant of awareness:\~ }{\i\insrsid8201588 He did it!\~ }{\insrsid8201588 There was no pain greater than the betrayal.\~ Hunting for a name that was not }{\i\insrsid8201588 Hoquat, }{\insrsid8201588 
the boy sank into blackness.
\par Katsuk felt anguish invade his breast.\~ He said:\~ "Soul Catcher, it is done."
\par Carefully measuring out each step, Katsuk advanced upon the shelter.\~ He stared at the arrow in Hoquat's breast.\~ Now, the circle was complete.\~ It had been a clean and shattering stroke, straight through the heart and probably into the spine.\~
 Death had come quickly to the Innocent.
\par Katsuk felt the ancient watchers of the spirit world departing then.\~ He stood alone, immobile, fascinated by his own creation -- this death.
\par In the growing daylight, the folds of the boy's clothing took on a semblance of the mossy post behind the body.\~ Part of the body appeared ready to dissipate into the smoke winding upward from the fire pit.\~ It created an illusion of 
transparency about Hoquat.\~ The boy was gone.\~ The Innocent had left this place in company with the ancient watchers.\~ That was as it should be.
\par Katsuk heard the searchers then.\~ They were climbing onto the logs which crossed the river.\~ They would be here within minutes.\~ What did it matter now?
\par Tears coursed down Katsuk's cheeks.\~ He dropped the bow, stumbled forward across the fire pit, fell to his knees, and gathered up the small body.
\par }{\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid8201588\charrsid8201588 When Sheriff Pallatt and the search party entered the clearing at th
e shelter, Katsuk sat with Hoquat's body in his arms, cradling the dead boy like a child, swaying and chanting the death song one sang for a friend.\~ The white down of the sea ducks floated in the damp air all around them.
